Berg)\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Wonderland (U.S. TV series)|Wonderland]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Creator;<br>Episode \"Pilot\"\n|- \n| 2006\n| ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|executive}} \n| {{yes}}\n| Creator;<br>Episodes \"Pilot\" and \"East of Dillon\"\n|- \n|rowspan=3| 2009\n| ''[[30 for 30]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| Episode \"Kings Ransom\"\n|-\n| ''[[Virtuality (TV series)|Virtuality]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| {{no}}\n| TV movie\n|-\n| ''[[Trauma (U.S. TV series)|Trauma]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Prime Suspect (US TV series)|Prime Suspect]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| {{no}}\n|Episode \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]''  \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| {{no}}\n|Episodes \"Pilot\" and \"Penguin One, Us Zero\"\n|-\n| 2015-2019\n| ''[[Ballers]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| {{no}}\n| Episode \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The People's Fighters: Teofilo Stevenson and the Legend of Cuban Boxing]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| TV documentary, also narrator\n|- \n| 2019\n| ''[[Dare Me (TV series)|Dare Me]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| TBA\n|''[[The Green Beret\u2019s Guide to Surviving the Apocalypse|The Green Beret\u2019s Guide<br>to Surviving the Apocalypse]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n====Acting roles====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[21 Jump Street]]''  \n| Jerome Sawyer\n| Episode \"Champagne High\"\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Fallen Angels (American TV series)|Fallen Angels]]'' \n| \n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1995-1999\n| ''[[Chicago Hope]]''\n| Dr. Billy Kronk\n| 106 episodes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[The Naked Truth (TV series)|The Naked Truth]]''\n| \n| 1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2002\n| ''[[The King of Queens]]''\n| Lil' Eddie\n| Episode \"Kirbed Enthusiasm\"\n|-\n| ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]''\n| Agent Noah Hicks\n| Episodes \"Snowman\" and \"Masquerade\"\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]''\n| Morris \"Mo\" McArnold\n| Episode \"May The Best Man Win\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]''\n| Himself\n| Season 5 and Season 7\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''\n| Himself\n| Episode \"The Way of the Fist\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]''\n| Pete\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Ballers]]''\n| Dolphins Coach\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n|-\n| 2003\n| \"[[Addicted (Enrique Iglesias song)|Addicted]]\"\n| [[Enrique Iglesias]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| \"[[Keeps Gettin' Better#Music video|Keeps Gettin' Better]]\" \n| [[Christina Aguilera]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| \"[[One More Night (Maroon 5 song)|One More Night]]\" \n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Maroon 5]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| \"[[Maps (Maroon 5 song)|Maps]]\"\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Film !! Result\n|-\n| 1996 || rowspan=3|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]] || rowspan=3|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series]] || rowspan=3|''[[Chicago Hope]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1997 || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4|1998 || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Deauville American Film Festival|Deauville American Film Festival Award]] || Fun Radio Trophy || rowspan=3|''[[Very Bad Things]]'' || {{won}}\n|-\n| Grand Special Prize || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival|San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival Award]] || Golden Seashell || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=5|2005 || [[American Film Institute#AFI Awards|AFI Award]] || Movie of the Year || rowspan=7|''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]'' || {{won}}\n|-\n| [[ESPY Award]] || Best Sports Movie || {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award]] || Choice Movie: Drama || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[USC Scripter Award]] || Best Film<br><small>(Shared with [[Buzz Bissinger]] and David Aaron Cohen)</small>|| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Young Artist Award]] || Best Family Feature Film - Drama || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2007 || [[Primetime Emmy Award]] || [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America]] || Best New Series<br><small>(Shared with [[Bridget Carpenter]], [[Kerry Ehrin]], [[Carter Harris]],<br>[[Liz Heldens]], [[David Hudgins]], [[Jason Katims]], [[Patrick Massett]],<br>[[Andy Miller (US writer)|Andy Miller]], [[Aaron Rahsaan Thomas]] and [[John Zinman]])</small>|| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Golden Eagle Award (Russia)|Golden Eagle Award]] || [[Golden Eagle Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Film]] || ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2011 || [[Primetime Emmy Award]] || [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]] || ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=5|2013 || rowspan=2|[[Golden Raspberry Award]] || [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] || rowspan=4|''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Trailer Award]] || Best Summer Blockbuster 2012 TV Spot || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Houston Film Critics Society|Houston Film Critics Society Award]] || Worst Film || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award]] || [[Satellite Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] || rowspan=3|''[[Lone Survivor]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2014 || [[Writers Guild of America Award]] || [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]] || [[Saturn Award for Best Director|Best Director]] || {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|916}}\n*{{Amg name|5586}}\n*[http://www.kcrw.com/music/programs/gd/gd080618peter_berg Peter Berg's KCRW Guest DJ Set]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/14/arts/television/14wond.html?ref=television The New York Times: Wonderland]\n\n{{Peter Berg}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berg, Peter}}\n[[Category:Taft School alumni]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York City]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Macalester College alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Showrunners]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Action film directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the American filmmaker and actor|the environmental writer|Peter Berg (bioregionalist)}}\n{{short description|American actor and director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Peter Berg\n| image = Peter Berg by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption = Berg speaking at [[Wondercon]] in March 2012\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|3|11|}}<ref name=\"IMDB-bio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000916|title=Peter Berg - IMDb |work=IMDb |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=2018-03-24}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| education = [[The Taft School]]\n| alma_mater = [[Macalester College]]\n| occupation = Director, producer, writer, actor\n| yearsactive = 1988\u2013present\n| notable_works = ''[[The Rundown]]'', ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]'', ''[[The Kingdom (film)|The Kingdom]]'', ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]'', ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'', ''[[Lone Survivor]]'', ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'', ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''\n| spouse = {{marriage|Elizabeth Rogers<br />|1993|1998|end=div}}\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''Peter Berg''' (born March 11, 1964) is an American director, producer, writer, and actor. His directorial film works include the black comedy ''[[Very Bad Things]]'' (1998), the action comedy ''[[The Rundown]]'' (2003), the sports drama ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2004), the action thriller ''[[The Kingdom (film)|The Kingdom]]'' (2007), the superhero comedy-drama ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]'' (2008), the military science fiction war film ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'' (2012), the war film ''[[Lone Survivor]]'' (2013), the disaster drama ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'' (2016), the [[Boston Marathon bombing]] drama ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]'' (2016) and the action thriller ''[[Mile 22]]'' (2018), the latter four all starring [[Mark Wahlberg]]. In addition to cameo appearances in the last six of these titles, he has had prominent acting roles in films including ''[[The Great White Hype]]'' (1996), ''[[Cop Land]]'' (1997), ''[[Corky Romano]]'' (2001), ''[[Collateral (film)|Collateral]]'' (2004), ''[[Smokin' Aces]]'' (2006), and ''[[Lions for Lambs]]'' (2007).\n\nIn television, Berg developed ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2006\u20132011), adapted from his film, earning two [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations. As an actor, he is best known for his role as Dr. Billy Kronk on the [[CBS]] [[medical drama]] ''[[Chicago Hope]]'' (1995\u20131999).<ref>{{cite news |url= https://movies.nytimes.com/person/1548578/Peter-Berg |title= Peter Berg |work= [[The New York Times]] |date= 2007-01-18 |accessdate= 2011-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBerg was born in 1964 in New York City, the son of Laurence \"Larry\",<ref>{{cite web|date= May 3, 2015|title=Laurence Berg obituary|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?pid=174771896}}</ref> a US Marine, and Sally (Winkler) Berg.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ad-meter/2017/02/06/hyundais-live-commercial-puts-deployed-soldiers-super-bowl-families/97538310/|title=Ad Meter|author=|date=|website=Ad Meter}}</ref> Berg's father was [[Jewish]], as was his maternal grandfather.<ref>http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/31476/celebrity-jews/</ref> His mother was Christian.<ref>http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/hollywood_now_drew_barrymore_makes_you_want_to_call_your_best_friend_and_bridget_moynahan_gets_hitched/</ref>\n\nThrough his mother, Berg is a second cousin of writer [[Buzz Bissinger|H. G. Bissinger]], whose book ''[[Friday Night Lights (book)|Friday Night Lights]]'' provided the basis for Berg's film and TV series of the same name.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-02-28/features/9402280075_1_peter-berg-walking-neck/2 |title= Walking Tall |first= Bart |last=Mills|publisher=Chicago Tribune |date= 1994-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CAUGHT+IN+THE+CROSSFIRE+POLITICS%2c+RELIGION%2c+BLOCKBUSTER+ACTION+HOLD...-a0169256513|title=Caught in the Crossfire: Politics, Religion, Blockbuster Action Hold the Keys to This 'Kingdom'|publisher= Goliath.ecnext.com|accessdate=2011-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lights On or Off?|date=November 9, 2006|first=Ruth|last=Samuelson |work=[[Houston Press]]|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/news/lights-on-or-off-6544995}}</ref> His mother co-founded a youth group named Catalog for Giving and worked at a psychiatric hospital when Berg was growing up.<ref name=\"Yahoo-bio\">{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800026675/bio|title=Peter Berg Biography|work= Yahoo! Movies|publisher= [[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=2008-09-14}}</ref> He has a younger sister, Mary.\n\nPeter was a student in the Chappaqua School System. After graduating from [[The Taft School]] in 1980,<ref name=\"taft80\">The Taft School, [http://www.taftschool.org/news/video.aspx?storyname=headholiday09 Berg and Smith], taftschool.org; retrieved July 24, 2011.</ref> Berg attended [[Macalester College]] in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]], where he majored in theater arts and theater history. He graduated in 1984, and in 1985 moved to Los Angeles to pursue his film career.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Career==\nBerg put his acting aspirations on hold when he first arrived in Los Angeles, choosing instead to learn about the film business as a [[production assistant]]. He acted in ''[[21 Jump Street]]'' and ''Quiet Victory: The Charlie Wedemeyer Story'' (both in 1988). He acted in ''Never on Tuesday'', ''[[Miracle Mile (film)|Miracle Mile]]'', ''Race For Glory'', ''[[Shocker (film)|Shocker]]'', ''[[Heart of Dixie (film)|Heart of Dixie]]'', ''Tale of Two Sisters'' and ''[[Going Overboard]]'' in 1989. He acted in ''Genuine Risk'' and ''Forradalom ut\u00e1n'' in 1990. He appeared in ''[[Late for Dinner]]'' and ''[[Crooked Hearts]]'' in 1991. In the early 1990s, he appeared in ''[[A Midnight Clear]]'', ''A Case for Murder'', ''[[Fire in the Sky]]'', ''[[Aspen Extreme]]'', ''Across the Moon'', ''Uneviled'' and ''[[F.T.W. (film)|F.T.W.]]''\n\nIn 1992, Berg gained recognition for playing a [[World War II]] soldier in the film ''[[A Midnight Clear]]''. In 1998, Berg made his feature directorial debut with ''[[Very Bad Things]]'', a [[black comedy]] starring [[Jon Favreau]], [[Christian Slater]], [[Jeremy Piven]], [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]], and [[Leland Orser]]. The film, which was shown at the Toronto and San Sebastian Film Festivals, received mixed critical reception. In 2000, he created ''[[Wonderland (U.S. TV series)|Wonderland]]'', an edgy dramatic television series set in an asylum. While the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] show received rave reviews and garnered a cult following, it failed to deliver ratings and was quickly canceled.\n\nIn 2003, Berg directed the action comedy ''[[The Rundown]]''. Starring [[Dwayne \"The Rock\" Johnson]] and [[Seann William Scott]], the film received positive reviews from critics but disappointed at the box office, only grossing 80 million of its reported 85 million budget. In 2004, Berg began work on his third directorial effort, ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]'', a football film based on the [[New York Times]] bestseller written by [[Buzz Bissinger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviefone.com/celebrity/peter-berg/1147807/biography|title=Peter Berg Biography|publisher=Moviefone|accessdate=2011-09-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127024845/http://www.moviefone.com/celebrity/peter-berg/1147807/biography|archivedate=2012-01-27|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Berg developed and became executive producer of [[NBC]]\u2019s [[Peabody Award|Peabody]] and [[Emmy Award]]-winning drama ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'', based on the [[Friday Night Lights (book)|novel]] and [[Friday Night Lights (film)|film]] of the same name.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nHe appeared in the war film ''[[Lions for Lambs]]'' (2007) as Lt. Colonel Falco. Berg followed up in 2007 with ''[[The Kingdom (film)|The Kingdom]]'', a [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]]-produced action-political thriller set in [[Saudi Arabia]], starring [[Academy Award]] winners [[Jamie Foxx]] and [[Chris Cooper]], also with [[Jennifer Garner]] whom Berg met when he appeared in a two-part episode of ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'' where he played Garner's ex-boyfriend. Berg\u2019s film ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]'', starring [[Will Smith]], [[Charlize Theron]] and [[Jason Bateman]], was one of the highest grossing films of 2008.\n\nBerg directed the [[Hulu.com]] commercial featuring [[Alec Baldwin]], which both [[The New York Times]] and [[Time magazine]] named best spot of [[Super Bowl XLIII]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://30for30.espn.com/film/kings-ransom.html |title=ESPN 30 for 30 |publisher=30for30.espn.com |date=1988-08-09 |accessdate=2011-09-12}}</ref> In 2009, Berg directed a two-hour pilot movie for a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] television series ''[[Virtuality (TV series)|Virtuality]]''. Even though the show was not picked up for a full season, the pilot was released on DVD exclusively through [[Best Buy]]. Berg also directed the [[ESPN]] documentary \"[[30 for 30|Kings Ransom]]\" in 2009. Berg also wrote the film ''[[The Losers (film)|The Losers]]'' (2010).\n\nBerg also directed the science-fiction/action film ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'' (2012) and the war film ''[[Lone Survivor]]'' (2013), an adaptation of Marcus Lutrell's [[Lone Survivor (book)|book of the same name]].<ref name=\"beyondhollywood.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beyondhollywood.com/peter-berg-puts-lone-survivor-on-hold-to-sink-my-battleship|title=Peter Berg Puts Lone Survivor on Hold to Sink My Battleship}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' writer Justin Chang said Berg delivered \"his most serious-minded work to date with ''Lone Survivor''.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Lone Survivor\u2019 Review: Mark Wahlberg Stars in Peter Berg\u2019s Grueling War Drama|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/reviews/lone-survivor-review-1200820276/|first=Justin|last=Chang|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|accessdate=December 21, 2013|date=December 16, 2013}}</ref> Berg is developing a [[Hancock 2|sequel]] to ''Hancock'' and producing a live-action version of the graphic novel ''[[Hercules: The Thracian Wars#Film|Hercules: The Thracian Wars]]''.<ref name=\"imdb.com\">{{IMDb title|1267297|Hercules: The Thracian Wars}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Berg created the opening animation sequence for [[ESPN]]'s ''[[Monday Night Football]]''. The 80-second graphic featured [[Darth Vader]] (from ''[[Star Wars]]''), [[Pac-Man]], President [[Ronald Reagan]] and some highlights of ''MNF'' games from 1970-2012. In 2014, he directed the first two episodes of [[HBO]]'s ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]''.\n\nIn 2016, Berg directed the film ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'', based on the [[Deepwater Horizon explosion]]. Berg replaced director [[J. C. Chandor]], who had exited the film due to creative differences.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Peter Berg in Talks to Replace J.C. Chandor on 'Deepwater Horizon'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/peter-berg-talks-replace-jc-768622|accessdate=February 1, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 30, 2015}}</ref> That same year, he directed [[CBS Films]]' ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]'', about the [[Boston Marathon bombing]]. [[Mark Wahlberg]] starred in both films.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Peter Berg Eyes CBS Films\u2019 Boston Marathon Thriller \u2018Patriots\u2019 Day\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/peter-berg-boston-marathon-bombing-patriots-day-1201505349/|accessdate=February 26, 2016|work=variety.com|date=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Berg was asked to direct an ambitious commercial for ''[[Hyundai Motor Company|Hyundai]]'', recorded after the kickoff of [[Super Bowl LI]] and aired right after the game.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brady|first1=Erik|title=Hyundai's 'live' commercial puts deployed soldiers at Super Bowl with families|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ad-meter/2017/02/06/hyundais-live-commercial-puts-deployed-soldiers-super-bowl-families/97538310/|accessdate=February 2, 2017|work=usatoday.com|date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1993, Berg was married to Elizabeth Rogers, an agent for [[Calvin Klein]]; they divorced in 1998.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/29/style/fashion-hitches-a-ride-with-hollywood-s-shining-stars.html |title=Fashion Hitches a Ride With Hollywood's Shining Stars |last=Spindler |first=Amy M. |date=August 29, 1995 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/18/magazine/can-peter-berg-redeem-himself-after-battleship.html|title=Peter Berg Threw Himself Under a Bus. Now What?|website=The New York Times|first=Pat|last=Jordan|date=August 15, 2013|accessdate=October 6, 2016}}</ref> He had one child with her.\n\nOn July 15, 2015, Berg criticized [[ESPN]]'s decision to honor [[Caitlyn Jenner]] with the [[Arthur Ashe Courage Award]] with an Instagram post in which he shared a [[Facebook]] photo of Army veteran [[Gregory D. Gadson]] (a double amputee who played a role in Berg\u2019s ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'' film) alongside one of Jenner. It said: \u201cOne Man traded 2 legs for the freedom of the other to trade 2 balls for 2 boobs. Guess which Man made the cover of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', was praised for his courage by [[President Obama]] and is to be honored with the \u2018Arthur Ashe Courage Award\u2019 by ESPN?\u201d Along with the shared post, Berg commented, \"Yup.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tmz.com/2015/07/16/peter-berg-pissed-over-caitlyn-jenner-she-doesnt-deserve-the-praise/ |title=Peter Berg Pissed Over Caitlyn Jenner : She Doesn't Deserve the Praise |date=July 16, 2015 |website=[[TMZ]] |access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter Berg received significant criticism for the post, he later clarified his remarks, saying he had the utmost respect for Jenner and transgender individuals; however, he released another photo with statistics on veteran suicide, stating, \u201cI also believe that we don\u2019t give enough attention to our courageous returning war veterans, many of whom have sacrificed their bodies and mental health for our country and our principals [''sic''] \u2013 principals that include the freedom to live the life you want to live without persecution or abuse.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/16/peter-berg-caitlyn-jenner |title=Peter Berg says he has 'utmost respect' for Caitlyn Jenner in new Instagram post |last=Rosen |first=Christopher |date=July 16, 2015 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n!width=65| [[Film director|Director]]\n!width=65| [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n!width=65| [[Film producer|Producer]]\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n|- \n| 1998\n| ''[[Very Bad Things]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| Also composer (\"Walls Come Down\")\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[The Rundown]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|- \n| 2004\n| ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n|- \n| 2007\n| ''[[The Kingdom (film)|The Kingdom]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n|- \n| 2008\n| ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Losers (film)|The Losers]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Lone Survivor]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|- \n|rowspan=2|2016\n| ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''\n| {{yes}} \n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Mile 22]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|- \n| 2020\n| ''[[Spenser Confidential]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Producer only'''\n* ''[[Pu-239 (film)|Pu-239]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Lars and the Real Girl]]'' (2007) (Executive producer)\n* ''[[Hell or High Water (2016 film)|Hell or High Water]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Wind River (film)|Wind River]]'' (2017)\n\n====Acting roles====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''Quiet Victory: The Charlie Wedemeyer Story''  \n| Bobby\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=7| 1989\n| ''Never on Tuesday''\n| Eddie\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Miracle Mile (film)|Miracle Mile]]'' \n| Band Member\n|\n|-\n| ''Race For Glory''\n| Chris Washburn\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Shocker (film)|Shocker]]''\n| Jonathan Parker\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Heart of Dixie (film)|Heart of Dixie]]''\n| Jenks\n|\n|-\n| ''Tale of Two Sisters''\n| Gardner\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Going Overboard]]'' \n| Mort Ginsberg\n| as Pete Berg\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1990\n| ''Genuine Risk''\n| Henry\n|\n|-\n| ''Forradalom ut\u00e1n''\n| \n| \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1991\n| ''[[Late for Dinner]]'' \n| Frank Lovegren\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Crooked Hearts]]'' \n| Tom\n| \n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[A Midnight Clear]]''\n| Bud Miller\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=3| 1993\n| ''A Case for Murder''\n| Jack Hemmet\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Fire in the Sky]]''\n| David Whitlock\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Aspen Extreme]]''\n| Dexter Rutecki\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=5| 1994 \n|''Across the Moon''\n| Lyle\n| \n|-\n| ''Uneviled''\n| Drug dealer \n| \n|-\n| ''[[F.T.W. (film)|F.T.W.]]''\n| Clem Stuart\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Last Seduction]]''\n| Mike Swale\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Rise and Walk: The Dennis Byrd Story]]''\n| [[Dennis Byrd]]\n| \n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Heavyweights]]''\n| Chef (uncredited)\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1996\n| ''[[The Great White Hype]]''\n| Terry Conklin\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Girl 6 (film)|Girl 6]]''\n| Caller No 1\u2014Bob\n| \n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Cop Land]]''\n| Joey Randone\n| \n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Very Bad Things]]''\n| Doctor\n| \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Dill Scallion]]''\n| Nate Clumson\n| \n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Corky Romano]]''\n| Paulie Romano\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Collateral (film)|Collateral]]''\n| Richard Weidner\n| \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Smokin' Aces]]''\n| \"Pistol\" Pete Deeks\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2007\n| ''[[Lions for Lambs]]''\n| Lt. Col. Falco\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Kingdom (film)|The Kingdom]]''\n| FBI Agent\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]''\n| Doctor\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[POM Wonderful Presents: The Greatest Movie Ever Sold|POM Wonderfu