{"title_page": "Devin McCourty", "text_new": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name = Devin McCourty\n| image = Devin McCourty.JPG\n| image_size = 200\n| alt =\n| caption = McCourty with the Patriots in 2011\n| number = 32\n| current_team = New England Patriots\n| position = [[Safety (American and Canadian football position)|Free safety]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|8|13|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Nyack, New York]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lbs = 195\n| high_school = [[Saint Joseph Regional High School|Saint Joseph Regional]]<br />([[Montvale, New Jersey]])\n| college = [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]]\n| draftyear = 2010\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 27\n| pastteams =\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2013present)\n|status=Active\n| highlights =\n* 3\u00d7 [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]], [[Super Bowl LI|LI]], [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2011 Pro Bowl|2010]], [[2017 Pro Bowl|2016]])\n* 3\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2010 All-Pro Team|2010]], [[2013 All-Pro Team|2013]], [[2016 All-Pro Team|2016]])\n* First-team All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] (2009)\n| statweek = \n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1 = [[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n| statvalue1 = 772\n| statlabel2 = [[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2 = 3.0\n| statlabel3 = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n| statvalue3 = 11\n| statlabel4 = [[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n| statvalue4 = 6\n| statlabel5 = [[Interceptions]] \n| statvalue5 = 26\n| statlabel6 = [[Touchdown|Total touchdowns]]\n| statvalue6 = 2\n| statlabel7 = [[Pass deflections]]\n| statvalue7 = 87\n| nfl = MCC600258\n| pfr = McCoDe99 \n}}\n'''Devin McCourty''' (born August 13, 1987) is an [[American football]] [[free safety]] for the [[New England Patriots]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]], and was drafted by the Patriots in the first round of the [[2010 NFL Draft]].\n\n\n==High school career==\nMcCourty attended [[Saint Joseph Regional High School]] in [[Montvale, New Jersey]], with his twin brother, [[Jason McCourty]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/gallery/2012/before_they_were_patriots?pg=16 |title=Before they were Patriots |accessdate=January 27, 2011 |work=The Boston Globe |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120130002206/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/gallery/2012/before_they_were_patriots?pg=16 |archivedate=January 30, 2012 }}.</ref> He played cornerback and [[free safety]] and was an all-league selection in his final two seasons. As a senior, he had 50 tackles and three interceptions.\n\nConsidered a two-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], McCourty only received one scholarship offer, from Rutgers.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Devin-McCourty-28858;_ylt=AtVwcCNAZc0.thHCHZL1vtVDPZB4 Devin McCourty Recruiting Profile]</ref>\n\n==College career==\nMcCourty attended [[Rutgers University]], and played for the [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football]] team beginning in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1.html |title=Devin McCourty College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> After [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]]ing his first season, McCourty appeared in all 13 games as a freshman in 2006 and recorded 38 tackles and two interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1/gamelog/2006/ |title=Devin McCourty 2006 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In 2007, McCourty and his twin brother [[Jason McCourty]] started at cornerback, with Devin compiling 63 tackles, two interceptions, one forced fumble, and three blocked kicks on [[special teams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1/gamelog/2007/ |title=Devin McCourty 2007 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> He was named an All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Conference]] academic selection in his first two seasons.\n\nMcCourty started 13 games at cornerback in his 2008 junior season, picking up 57 tackles, one interception, and a blocked punt.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1/gamelog/2008/ |title=Devin McCourty 2008 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> \nIn his final season at Rutgers in 2009, McCourty started 13 games at cornerback, while still also working on special teams units. He had a career-high 80 tackles and also recorded one interception and 10 pass deflections. He also averaged 25.4 yards on kickoff returns and had a 98-yard kickoff return, third-longest in school history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1/gamelog/2009 |title=Devin McCourty 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> Following the season, he was named to the All-Big East first team.\n\nMcCourty graduated from Rutgers with a bachelor's degree in sociology.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/21/sports/ncaafootball/21rutgers.html?_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Dave | last=Caldwell | title=The McCourty Twins, Divided Between Rutgers and the N.F.L | date=November 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"2\"|Games !! colspan=\"4\"|Tackles !! colspan=\"4\"|Interceptions\n|-\n! G !! GS !! Comb !! Total !! Ast !! Sack !! Int !! Yards !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n! [[2006 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2006]] !! [[2006 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]]\n| 13 || 13 || 38 || 23 || 15 || 0.5 || 2 || 69 || 34.5 || 1 \n|-\n! [[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007]] !! [[2007 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]]\n| 13 || 13 || 63 || 40 || 23 || 0.5 || 2 || 36 || 18.0 || 1\n|- \n! [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]] !! [[2008 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]]\n| 13 || 13 || 57 || 37 || 20 || 0.0 || 1 || 0 || 0.0 || 0\n|- \n! [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]] !! [[2009 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]]\n| 13 || 13 || 80 || 49 || 31 || 0.0 || 1 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 \n|- \n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 52 !! 52 !! 238 !! 149 !! 89 !! 1.0 !! 6 !! 105 !! 17.5 !! 2 \n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nOn August 25, 2009, NFL analyst [[Gil Brandt]] ranked McCourty the fourth best cornerback prospect heading into the 2010 NFL Draft.<ref>{{cite web| title=Senior class of cornerbacks solid heading into 2010 draft| url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d81223ec6/article/senior-class-of-cornerbacks-solid-heading-into-2010-draft| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com| author=Brandt, Gil| date=August 25, 2010}}</ref> He attended the [[NFL Scouting Combine]] and performed all of the combine drills. On March 10, 2010, McCourty attended Rutger's annual pro day, but chose to stand on his combine numbers and only performed positional drills. At the conclusion of the pre-draft process, McCourty was projected to be a first or second round pick by NFL draft experts and scouts.<ref>{{cite web| title=2010 NFL Draft Scouting Report: Devin McCourty| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/348072-2010-nfl-draft-scouting-report-devin-mccourty| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com}}</ref> He was ranked third best cornerback prospect in the draft by [[Sports Illustrated]] and [[ESPN]], was ranked the fourth best cornerback by DraftScout.com, and was ranked the fifth best cornerback in the draft by [[Bleacher Report]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Devon McCourty, DS #3 CB, Rutgers| url=http://draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=75877&draftyear=2010&genpos=CB| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=Draftscour.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Top 10 Cornerbacks in the NFL Draft| url=https://www.si.com/nfl/photos/2010/04/16-0top-10-cornerbacks-in-the-nfl-draft#3| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=si.com| author=Burke, Chris| date=April 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=2010 NFL Draft: Cornerback Rankings| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/348720-2010-nfl-draft-cornerback-rankings| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Nally, Zach| date=February 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=The top 100 players in 2010 NFL draft| url=http://www.thestate.com/sports/college/university-of-south-carolina/usc-football/article18139145.html| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=thestate.com| author=Legwold, Jeff| date=April 18, 2010}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/09000d5d816dd9ca/2010-Combine-workout-Devin-McCourty Devin McCourty's NFL Combine Workout]\n}}\n{{nfl predraft\n| height ft = 5\n| height in = 10\u00be\n| weight = 193\n| dash = 4.48\n| ten split = 1.60\n| twenty split = 2.65\n| shuttle = 4.07\n| cone drill = 6.70\n| vertical = 36\n| broad ft = 10\n| broad in = 6\n| bench = 16\n| wonderlic = \n| arm span = 32\n| hand span = 9\n| note = All values from [[NFL Combine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/devin-mccourty?id=494287|title=Devin McCourty Combine Profile|work=NFL.com|accessdate=April 10, 2010}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=75877&draftyear=2010&genpos=CB|title=Devin McCourty Draft Profile|work=NFLDraftScout.com|accessdate=April 10, 2010}}.</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010===\nThe [[New England Patriots]] selected McCourty in the first round (27th overall) of the [[2010 NFL Draft]]. He was the third cornerback drafted in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2010/draft.htm |title=2010 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> \n{{external media\n| video1 = [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=o4AfuWmOkAw Patriots draft McCourty 27th overall]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-videos/09000d5d8177f4c3/comments/2010-Draft-Vignettes-Devin-McCourty-Rutgers 2010 NFL Draft Vignette: Devin McCourty]\n}}\nOn July 28, 2010, the New England Patriots signed McCourty to a five-year, [[United States dollar|$]]10 million contract that includes $7.28 million guaranteed and a [[signing bonus]] of $1.50 million.<ref>{{cite web| title=Contract Details on Devin McCourty| url=https://www.patspulpit.com/2010/7/28/1592046/contract-details-on-devin-mccourty| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=patspulpit.com| author=Knopping, Greg| date=July 28, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/nfl/news/story?id=5416241|title=Devin McCourty agrees to deal|work=ESPNBoston.com|first=Mike|last=Reiss|date=July 28, 2010|accessdate=July 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"spotrac\">{{cite web| title=Spotrac.com: Devin McCourty contract| url=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/new-england-patriots/devin-mccourty-6536/| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=Spotrac.com}}</ref>\n\nUpon him arriving in training camp, McCourty began competing for a job as a starting cornerback against [[Darius Butler]]. Head coach [[Bill Belichick]] named both McCourty and Darius Butler the starting cornerbacks to begin the regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 09/06/2010| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/111/NE| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| \ntitle=PATRIOTS FOOTBALL: Starting CB Bodden placed on IR| url=https://www.middletownpress.com/news/article/PATRIOTS-FOOTBALL-Starting-CB-Bodden-placed-on-IR-11879131.php| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=middletownpress.com| author=Associated Press| date=August 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe made his professional regular season debut and first career start in the [[2010 New England Patriots|New England Patriots']] season-opener against the [[2010 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]] and recorded five solo tackles and a pass deflection in their 38\u201324 victory.<ref name=\"stats10\"/> McCourty made his first career tackle on [[Adam Jones (American football)|Adam Jones]], ending Jones 19-yard kick return in the first quarter.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 1-2010: Cincinnati Bengals @ New England Patriots| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2010091202/2010/REG1/bengals@patriots#tab=recap| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> On October 24, 2010, McCourty made three combined tackles, a pass deflection, and made his first career interception off a pass by quarterback [[Philip Rivers]] during a 23\u201320 win at the [[2010 San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] in Week 7.<ref name=\"stats10\"/> McCourty intercepted the pass that was originally intended for [[Patrick Crayton]] in the second quarter and was immediately tackled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201010240sdg.htm |title=New England Patriots at San Diego Chargers - October 24th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On November 14, 2010, he collected a season-high 11 combined tackles (nine solo) and broke up a pass in the Patriots' 39\u201326 victory at the [[2010 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh]] in Week 10.<ref name=\"stats10\"/> In Week 11, he collected six combined tackles, two pass deflections, and an interception in the Patriots' 31\u201328 win against the [[2010 Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref name=\"stats10\"/> The following week, McCourty made a season-high three pass deflections, seven combined tackles, and intercepted two passes by [[Matthew Stafford]] in a 45\u201324 victory at the [[2010 Detroit Lions|Detroit Lions]] in Week 12. The feat marked his first multi-interception game of his career.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201011250det.htm |title=New England Patriots at Detroit Lions - November 25th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On December 6, 2010, McCourty recorded three solo tackles, broke up a pass, and an interception as the Patriots routed the [[2010 New York Jets|New York Jets]] 45\u20133 in Week 13.<ref name=\"stats10\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2010)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2010| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> The interception was his sixth pick of the season and continued his three-game streak with an interception. In Week 15, he collected ten solo tackles (seven solo), a pass deflection, and made his first career sack on quarterback [[Aaron Rodgers|Matt Flynn]] during a 31\u201327 win against the [[2010 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012190nwe.htm |title=Green Bay Packers at New England Patriots - December 19th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On December 29, 2010, it was announced that McCourty was voted to the [[2011 Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web| title=2011 Pro Bowl: Tom Brady, Vince Wilfork, Devin McCourty Headline Patriots| url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2010/12/29/1901911/2011-pro-bowl-tom-brady-vince-wilfork-devin-mccourty-patriots| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=SBNation.com| author=Thorman, Joel| date=December 29, 2010}}</ref> He finished his rookie season in 2010 with 82 combined tackles (69 solo), 17 pass deflections, seven interceptions, two forced fumbles, and a sack in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref name=\"career\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (career)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/careerstats| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> His 17 pass deflections and seven interceptions marked career-highs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/Players/M/McCoDe99/gamelog/2010/ |title=Devin McCourty 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> McCourty was named a First-Team [[All-Pro]] by the [[Sporting News]] and Second-Team All-Pro by [[The Associated Press]].\n\nThe New England Patriots finished first in the [[AFC East]] with a 14\u20132 record and clinched home-field advantage and a first round bye. On January 16, 2011, McCourty started in his first career playoff game and collected three solo tackles in their 28\u201321 loss to the [[2010 New York Jets|New York Jets]] in the AFC Divisional Round.<ref name=\"stats10\"/> On January 30, 2011, he appeared in the 2011 Pro Bowl and recorded four solo tackles, two pass deflections, and intercepted a pass by [[Michael Vick]]. He was part of Bill Belichick's AFC team that lost 55\u201341 to the NFC.<ref name=\"stats10\"/>\n\n===2011===\nMcCourty entered training camp slated as the Patriots' No. 1 starting cornerback.<ref>{{cite web| title=Devin McCourty and Leigh Bodden, New England Patriots' Super Bowl Caliber CBs | url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/800577-devin-mccourty-and-leigh-bodden-new-england-patriots-super-bowl-caliber-cbs| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Dimaio, James| date=August 12, 2011}}</ref> Head coach Bill Belichick officially named McCourty the starter, alongside Leigh Bodden, to start the regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 09/04/2011| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/123/NE| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> On September 8, 2011, it was reported that McCourty was selected by teammates to be one of the six team captains. McCourty, [[Jerod Mayo]], and [[Vince Wilfork]] were chosen to be defensive captains for the season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Report: Patriots Name 2011 Captains| url=https://www.patspulpit.com/platform/2011/9/8/2412383/report-patriots-name-2011-captains| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=patspulpit.com| author=Knopping, Greg| date=September 8, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nMcCourty started in [[2011 New England Patriots|New England Patriots']] season-opener at the [[2011 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]] and collected a season-high 11 combined tackles (ten solo) and two pass deflections in their 38\u201324 victory. On November 13, 2011, he made four solo tackles during 37\u201316 victory at the [[2011 New York Jets|New York Jets]], but exited in the second quarter after injuring his shoulder during a collision with teammate [[Sterling Moore]]. His shoulder injury sidelined him for the next two games (Weeks 11\u201312).<ref>{{cite web| title=Devin McCourty suffers shoulder injury| url=http://www.espn.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/7232153/new-england-patriots-devin-mccourty-injures-shoulder-new-york-jets| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=ESPN.com| date=November 14, 2011}}</ref> In Week 16, McCourty collected nine combined tackles, a season-high five pass deflections, and made an interception during a 27\u201324 victory. He finished the {{NFL Year|2011}} season with 87 combined tackles (65 solo), 13 pass deflections, and two interceptions in 14 games and 14 starts.<ref name=\"career\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McCoDe99/gamelog/2011/ |title=Devin McCourty 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe New England Patriots finished first in the AFC East with a 13\u20133 record. They went on to defeat the [[2011 Denver Broncos|Denver Broncos]] 45\u201310 in the AFC Divisional Round and the [[2011 Baltimore Ravens|Baltimore Ravens]] 23\u201320 in the AFC Championship to advance to the Super Bowl. On February 5, 2012, McCourty started in [[Super Bowl XLVI]] and collected seven combined tackles as the Patriots lost to the [[New York Giants]] by a score of 21\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201202050nwe.htm |title=Super Bowl XLVI - New York Giants vs. New England Patriots - February 5th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\nMcCourty entered training camp slated as the No. 1 starting cornerback.<ref>{{cite web| title=Analyzing 2012 Patriots Roster| url=http://www.espn.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4721463/analyzing-2012-patriots-roster| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=ESPN.com| author=Rodak, Mike| date=April 30, 2012}}</ref> Defensive coordinator [[Matt Patricia]] named McCourty and [[Kyle Arrington]] the starting cornerbacks to start the season, ahead of [[Ras-I Dowling]], [[Will Allen (cornerback)|Will Allen]], [[Sterling Moore]], and [[Alfonzo Dennard]]. He was also named the starting kick returner by special teams coordinator [[Scott O'Brien]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 10/01/2012| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/136/NE| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> On September 6, 2012, it was announced that McCourty was selected to be a captain for the second consecutive season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots Name Six 2012 Team Captains| url=https://www.boston.cbslocal.com/2012/09/06/patriots-name-six-2012-team-captains/| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=boston.cbslocal.com| date=September 6, 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502165534/http://boston.cbslocal.com/2012/09/06/patriots-name-six-2012-team-captains/| archive-date=May 2, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 4, McCourty collected four solo tackles, two pass deflections, and intercepted two passes by quarterback [[Ryan Fitzpatrick]] during a 52\u201328 win at the [[2012 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 4-2012: New England Patriots @ Buffalo Bills| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2012093000/2012/REG4/patriots@bills| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> On October 21, 2012, McCourty made five solo tackles and returned a kick for a touchdown during a 29\u201326 overtime win against the [[2012 New York Jets|New York Jets]] in Week 7.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201210210nwe.htm |title=New York Jets at New England Patriots - October 21st, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> His kick return was for 104-yards and occurred in the first quarter. It became his first and only career kick return for a touchdown.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week7-2012: New York Jets @ Denver Broncos| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2012102108/2012/REG7/jets@patriots| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> His performance in Week 7 earned him AFC Special Teams Player of the Week. On November 1, 2012, the New England Patriots acquired cornerback [[Aqib Talib]] in a trade with the [[2012 Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000089499/article/new-england-patriots-move-devin-mccourty-to-safety|title=New England Patriots move Devin McCourty to safety|work=[[National Football League]]|date=November 4, 2012|accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref> Following the trade, it was reported that McCourty would be moving to free safety after struggling at cornerback during the first eight games.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots moving struggling DB McCourty to safety| url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2012/11/08/patriots-devin-mccourty-safety-ap| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=SI.com| date=November 8, 2012}}</ref> His move to safety was also attributed to injuries to safeties [[Steve Gregory (football player)|Steve Gregory]] and [[Patrick Chung]] and the emergence of Kyle Arrington and Alfonzo Dennard as productive cornerbacks.<ref>{{cite web| title=In new role, Devin McCourty provides a safety net| url=https://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2012/11/07/in-new-role-devin-mccourty-provides-a-safety-net| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=Boston.com| author=Whitmer, Michael| date=November 7, 2012}}</ref> McCourty immediately assumed the job as the starting free safety, replacing Patrick Chung, who was still recovering from a shoulder injury.<ref>{{cite web| title=Hernandez, Chung Out; 11 Questionable For Patriots Vs. Rams| url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2012/10/26/hernanez-chung-out-11-questionable-for-patriots-vs-rams/| accessdate=April 25, 2018| website=boston.cbslocal.com| date=October 26, 2012}}/</ref> On November 11, 2012, he made his debut as the starting free safety and recorded eight combined tackles, a pass deflection, and an interception in the Patriots' 37\u201331 win against the [[2012 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]] in Week 10.<ref name=\"stats12\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2012)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2012| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=April 27, 2018}}</ref> McCourty finished the {{NFL Year|2012}} season with 82 combined tackles (63 solo), 13 pass deflections, five interceptions, two forced fumbles, and a touchdown in 16 games and 16 starts. He started the last eight games at free safety and also served as the kick returner throughout the season. McCourty finished with 24 kick returns for a total of 654-yards and one touchdown.<ref name=\"career\"/> McCourty played a total of 1,329 snaps on defense and special teams. His snap total finished third in the league in 2012, behind teammates [[Ryan Wendell]] and [[Nate Solder]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.footballoutsiders.com/stats/snapcounts2012 |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203051518/http://www.footballoutsiders.com/stats/snapcounts2012 |archive-date=December 3, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[2012 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] completed the regular season in first place in the AFC East with a 12\u20134 record. On January 13, 2013, McCourty made his first postseason start at safety and collected eight combined tackles during a 41\u201328 win against the [[2012 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]] in the AFC Divisional Round.<ref name=\"stats12\"/> The following week, he made eight combined tackles as the Patriots were eliminated from the playoffs after a 28\u201313 loss to the [[2012 Baltimore Ravens|Baltimore Ravens]] in the AFC Championship Game.<ref name=\"stats12\"/>\n\n===2013===\nMcCourty began training camp as the ''de facto'' starting free safety after Patrick Chung departed in [[free agency (sports)|free agency]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Full Training Camp Roster Breakdown for Patriots| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1682910-full-training-camp-roster-breakdown-for-patriots| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Dessault, Mike| date=July 18, 2013}}</ref> He was named the starting free safety to open the regular season, alongside strong safety [[Steve Gregory]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 09/05/2013| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/150/NE| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> \nMcCourty was not selected as one of four team captains to begin the regular season. He became a captain, along with [[Rob Ninkovich]], mid-season after injuries to Mayo and Wilfork.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots Announce Team Captains: Dan Connolly the newest addition| url=https://www.patspulpit.com/platform/2014/9/3/6101251/patriots-announce-team-captains-dan-connolly-the-newest-addition| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=patspulpit.com| author=Knopping, Greg| date=September 3, 2014}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, 2013, McCourty collected a season-high 12 combined tackles (eight solo) during a 13\u20136 loss at the [[2013 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]] in Week 5.<ref name=\"stats13\"/> In Week 9, he made six combined tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass by [[Ben Roethlisberger]] in the Patriots' 55\u201331 win against the [[2013 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref name=\"stats13\"/> He was inactive for the Patriots' Week 17 victory against the [[2013 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]] after head coach Bill Belichick chose to rest him for the playoffs.<ref name=\"stats13\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2013)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2013| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> McCourty finished the season with 69 combined tackles (48 solo), nine pass deflections, and an interception in 15 games and 15 starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McCoDe99/gamelog/2013 |title=Devin McCourty 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref> He received the highest overall grade among all qualified safeties in 2013.<ref name=\"PFF\">{{cite web| title=Patriots Re-sign Devin McCourty| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/news/patriots-re-sign-devin-mccourty| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nMcCourty began the regular season as the starting free safety and played alongside strong safety Patrick Chung.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 10/01/2014| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/164/NE| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> This began a five-year stint where McCourty and Chung were the main starting safeties for the Patriots.\n\nIn Week 2, McCourty deflected a pass and also returned an interception for a 60-yard gain before being pushed out of bounds at the goal line during a 30\u20137 win at the [[2014 Minnesota Vikings|Minnesota Vikings]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409140min.htm |title=New England Patriots at Minnesota Vikings - September 14th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On November 30, 2014, McCourty collected a season-high nine combined tackles (eight solo) in the Patriots' 26\u201321 loss at the [[2014 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]] in Week 13.<ref name=\"stats14\"/> He finished the season with 68 combined tackles (51 solo), six pass deflections, two interceptions, and a forced fumble in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref name=\"career\"/> He earned the eighth highest overall grade from Pro Football Focus in 2015.<ref name=\"PFF\"/>\n\nThe [[2015 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] finished atop the AFC East with a 12\u20134 record, clinching a first round bye and home-field advantage. On January 10, 2015, he made four combined tackles, two pass deflections, and intercepted a pass by [[Joe Flacco]] during a 35-31 victory against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens|Baltimore Ravens]] in the AFC Divisional Round.<ref name=\"stats14\"/> The Patriots reached Super Bowl XLIX after routing the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis Colts]] 45\u20137 in the AFC Championship Game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501100nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots - January 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On February 1, 2015, McCourty collected five combined tackles and helped the Patriots defeat the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks|Seattle Seahawks]] 28\u201324 and win [[Super Bowl XLIX]].<ref name=\"stats14\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2014)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2014| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nMcCourty became an unrestricted free agent in 2015 and received interest from multiple teams, including the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], [[New York Giants]], [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], and [[Tennessee Titans]].<ref name=\"PFF\"/>\n\nOn March 9, 2015, the New England Patriots signed McCourty to a five-year, $47.5 million contract with $28.5 million guaranteed and a signing bonus of $15 million.<ref name=\"spotrac\"/><ref>http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/12446830/safety-devin-mccourty-re-sign-new-england-patriots-according-report</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4778888/breaking-down-devin-mccourtys-contract|title = Breaking down Devin McCourty's contract|last = Yates|first = Field|date = March 9, 2015|work = |access-date = March 9, 2015|publisher = ESPNBoston.com}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 6, McCourty collected a season-high nine combined tackles during a 34\u201327 win at the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis Colts]]. On October 29, 2015, he made four solo tackles and sacked quarterback [[Ryan Tannehill]] in New England's 36\u20137 win against the [[2015 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]] in Week 8. The sack became only the second one of his career and was his first sack since his rookie season.<ref name=\"stats15\"/> On December 13, 2015, McCourty made one tackle before exiting the Patriots' 27\u20136 victory at the [[2015 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]] in the second quarter due to an ankle injury.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots safety Devin McCourty leaves game with ankle injury| url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2015/12/13/devin-mccourty-injury-update-ankle-patriots| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=SI.com}}</ref> His injury sidelined him for the next two games (Weeks 15\u201316). He registered 64 combined tackles (51 solo), six passes defensed, one sack, and an interception in 14 games and 14 starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McCoDe99/gamelog/2015 |title=Devin McCourty 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The Patriots began deploying [[Duron Harmon]] in a three-safety technique at the end of the season.\n\nThe [[2015 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] finished atop their division with a 12\u20134 record. They defeated the [[2015 Kansas City Chiefs|Kansas City Chiefs]] in the AFC Divisional Round, before losing to the eventual [[Super Bowl 50|Super Bowl 50 Champions]], the [[2015 Denver Broncos|Denver Broncos]], in the AFC Championship Game.<ref name=\"stats15\"/> McCourty made seven combined tackles and two pass deflections throughout the playoffs with only two tackles and one deflection against the Broncos.<ref name=\"stats15\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2015)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2015| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn September 6, 2016, the New England Patriots announced the selection of McCourty as one of four team captains to start the regular season. It was his third consecutive selection and fifth overall.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots 2016 team captains include Rob Gronkowski, Dont\u2019a Hightower, but not Tom Brady|url=http://www.patspulpit.com/2016/9/6/12822914/patriots-announce-team-captains-2016-including-rob-gronkowski-donta-hightower-slater-brady-mccourty|author=Hill, Rich|website=PatsPulpit.com|date=September 6, 2016|accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe started in the [[2016 New England Patriots|New England Patriots']] season-opener at the [[2016 Arizona Cardinals|Arizona Cardinals]] and recorded a season-high ten combined tackles (nine solo) in their 23\u201321 victory. On December 12, 2016, McCourty made four solo tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass by [[Joe Flacco]] during a 30\u201323 win against the [[2016 Baltimore Ravens|Baltimore Ravens]] in Week 14.<ref name=\"stats16\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2016)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2016| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com}}/</ref> On December 20, McCourty was named to the [[2017 Pro Bowl]], his second time receiving the honor. He finished the season with 83 combined tackles (67 solo), seven pass deflections, an interception, and a forced fumble in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref name=\"career\"/> At the end of the season he was named second-team [[2016 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Three rookies, Matt Ryan among players named to All-Pro team|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000770458/article/three-rookies-matt-ryan-among-players-named-to-allpro-team?campaign=Twitter_atn|website=NFL.com|date=January 6, 2017}}</ref> He played 1022 defensive snaps (98%).<ref>{{cite web| title=Pro-Football Reference: New England Patriots Snap Count (2016)| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2016-snap-counts.htm| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=pro-football-reference.com}}</ref> He received an overall grade of 89.6 from Pro Football Focus and had the fourth highest grade among all qualified safeties in 2016. He also earned a coverage grade of 91.9.<ref>{{cite web| title=Safety Devin McCourty remains key to Patriots' defense| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/news/pro-devin-mccourty-remains-key-to-patriots-defense| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com| author=Gellar, Cyrus| date=May 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2016 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] finished first in their division with a 14\u20132 record and earned home-field advantage.<ref name=\"stats16\"/> On January 14, 2017, McCourty made five combined tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass during a 34\u201316 victory against the [[2016 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]] in the AFC Divisional Round.<ref name=\"stats16\"/> The Patriots went on to Super Bowl LI after defeating the [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]] 36\u201317 in the AFC Championship Game.<ref name=\"stats16\"/> On February 5, 2017, McCourty started in [[Super Bowl LI]] and made five combined tackles as the Patriots defeated the [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] 34\u201328 in overtime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm|title=Super Bowl LI - New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons - February 5th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=September 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2017020500/2016/POST22/patriots@falcons#menu=gameinfo%7CcontentId%3A0ap3000000783776&tab=analyze&analyze=boxscore|title=Watch New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons [02/05/2017]|work=NFL.com|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm|title=Super Bowl LI - New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons - February 5th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n[[File:Super Bowl 1F2868F4.jpg|thumb|McCourty in [[Super Bowl LII]]]]\nMcCourty and Patrick Chung remained the starting safety duo with [[Duron Harmon]] acting as the third safety to begin the regular season. In Week 5, he collected a season-high 11 solo tackles during a 19\u201314 victory at the [[2017 Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref name=\"stats17\"/> The following week, he made five combined tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass by [[Josh McCown]] in the Patriots' 24\u201317 victory at the [[2017 New York Jets|New York Jets]] in Week 6.<ref name=\"stats17\"/> On December 11, 2017, McCourty collected seven solo tackles and sacked quarterback [[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]] during a 27\u201320 loss at the [[2017 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]]. The sack became his third of his career.<ref name=\"stats17\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2017)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2017| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> McCourty finished the season with a career-high 97 combined tackles (80 solo), five pass deflections, an interception, and a sack in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref name=\"career\"/> [[Pro Football Focus]] gave McCourty an overall grade of 82.6, ranking 23rd among all qualified safeties in 2017.<ref>{{cite web| title=Pro Football Focus: Devin McCourty| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/nfl/players/devin-mccourty/5552| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref> The [[2017 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] finished first in the AFC East with a 13\u20133 record and received a first round bye and home-field advantage. They defeated the [[2017 Tennessee Titans|Tennessee Titans]] in the AFC Divisional Round and the [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars|Jacksonville Jaguars]] in the AFC Championship Game.<ref name=\"stats17\"/> On February 4, 2018, McCourty started in [[Super Bowl LII]] and collected seven combined tackles and two pass deflections in the Patriots' 41\u201333 loss to the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles|Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref name=\"stats17\"/>\n\n===2018===\nIn the preseason, Devin McCourty was reunited with his brother [[Jason McCourty]], who played as cornerback for the [[Tennessee Titans]] and the winless [[Cleveland Browns]] in 2017. Jason started as the number two cornerback in New England's secondary and formed a strong duo with All-Pro corner [[Stephon Gilmore]].\n\nIn Week 8 against the [[Buffalo Bills]], McCourty had an 84 yard pick six off [[Derek Anderson (American football)|Derek Anderson]] as the Patriots won the game 25-6. McCourty helped the Patriots win [[Super Bowl LIII]]. Overall in 2018 Mccourty had 1 interception for 23 yards and 82 tackles\n\n===2019===\nIn Week 1 against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], McCourty made his first interception of the season off [[Ben Roethlisberger]] in the endzone during the 33-3 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127860 |title=Brady starts his 20th season by beating Steelers 33-3 |date=8 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref> In Week 2 against the [[Miami Dolphins]], McCourty had his second interception of the season off of [[Ryan Fitzpatrick]] in the 43-0 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2019091505/2019/REG2/patriots@dolphins?icampaign=scoreStrip-globalNav-2019091505}}</ref>\nIn Week 3 against the [[New York Jets]], McCourty recorded his third interception of the season off [[Luke Falk]] in the 30-14 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127861 |title=Brady, Patriots defense shine in 30-14 win over Jets |date=22 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\nIn Week 4 against the [[Buffalo Bills]], McCourty intercepted his fourth pass of the season off [[Josh Allen (quarterback)|Josh Allen]] in the 16-10 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127866 |title=Patriots stay undefeated, hang on to beat Bills 16-10|date=29 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\nMcCourty became the first player to record 4 interceptions in a season's first 4 games since [[Minnesota Vikings]]' safety [[Brian Russell]] accomplished this feat in the 2003 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/devin-on-the-spot-patriots-mc-courty-now-has-four-interceptions-in-the-seasons-four-games-175146931.html |title=Devin on the spot: Patriots' McCourty now has four interceptions in the season's four games |last=Young |first=Shalise |date=29 September 2019 |website=www.sports.yahoo.com |access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> He was named AFC Defensive Player of the Month for September.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Buchmasser |first1=Bernd |title=Patriots safety Devin McCourty is the AFC Defensive Player of the Month for September |url=https://www.patspulpit.com/2019/10/3/20896743/new-england-patriots-safety-devin-mccourty-afc-defensive-player-of-the-month-september |website=PatsPulpit.com |publisher=Pats Pulpit |accessdate=October 3, 2019|date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 7 against the [[New York Jets]], McCourty recorded his fifth interception of the season off [[Sam Darnold]] in the 33-0 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127894 |title=Patriots blitz Darnold, Jets 33-0 to remain undefeated |date=20 October 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 8 against the [[Cleveland Browns]], McCourty recovered a fumble forced by teammate [[Jonathan Jones (American football)|Jonathan Jones]] on [[Nick Chubb]] in the 27-13 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127895 |title=Belichick wins 300th, perfect Patriots beat Browns 27-13 |date=27 October 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 14 against the [[Kansas City Chiefs]], McCourty forced a fumble on tight end [[Travis Kelce]] which was recovered by teammate [[Stephon Gilmore]] during the 23\u201316 loss. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127930 |title=KC survives mistakes, take AFC West with 23-13 win over Pats |date=December 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nOn March 17, 2020, McCourty signed a two-year, $23 million contract extension to stay with the Patriots.<ref>{{cite web|work=Patriots.com|url=https://www.patriots.com/news/report-devin-mccourty-signs-two-year-extension-with-patriots|date=March 15, 2020|title=Report: Devin McCourty signs two-year extension with Patriots|first=Mike|last=Dussault|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL career statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n| [[List of Super Bowl champions|Won the Super Bowl]]\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"2\"|Games !! colspan=\"4\"|Tackles !! colspan=\"6\"|Interceptions !! colspan=\"3\"|Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Comb !! Solo !! Ast !! Sack!! Int !! Yards !! Avg !! Long !! TD !! PD !! FF !! FR !! Yards \n|-\n! [[2010 NFL season|2010]] !! [[2010 New England Patriots season|NE]] \n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 82 || 69 || 13 || '''1.0''' || '''7''' || '''110''' || 15.7 || 50 || 0 || '''17''' || '''2''' || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2011 NFL season|2011]] !! [[2011 New England Patriots season|NE]] \n| 14 || 14 || 87 || 65 || 22 || 0.0 || 2 || 38 || 19.0 || 38 || 0 || 13 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2012 NFL season|2012]] !! [[2012 New England Patriots season|NE]] \n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 82 || 63 || 19 || 0.0 || 5 || 53 || 10.6 || 3 || 0 || 13 || '''2''' || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2013 NFL season|2013]] !! [[2013 New England Patriots season|NE]] \n| 15 || 15 || 69 || 48 || 21 || 0.0 || 1 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 9 || '''2''' || '''1''' || '''44'''\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] !! style=\"background:#afe6ba;|[[2014 New England Patriots season|NE]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 68 || 51 || 17 || 0.0 || 2 || 70 || 35.0 || 60 || 0 || 6 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] !! [[2015 New England Patriots season|NE]] \n| 14 || 14 || 64 || 51 || 13 || '''1.0''' || 1 || 27 || 27.0 || 27 || 0 || 6 || 0 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] !! style=\"background:#afe6ba;|[[2016 New England Patriots season|NE]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 83 || 67 || 16 || 0.0 || 1 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 7 || 1 || '''1''' || 3\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 New England Patriots season|NE]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || '''97''' || '''80''' || 17 || '''1.0 '''|| 1 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 5 || 0 || '''1''' || 0\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! style=\"background:#afe6ba;|[[2018 New England Patriots season|NE]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 82 || 59 || '''23''' || 0.0 || 1 || 84 || '''84.0''' || '''84T''' || '''1''' || 4 || 1 || 2 || 14\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 New England Patriots season|NE]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 58 || 46 || 12 || 0.0 || 5 || 49 || 9.8 || 24 || 0 || 7 || 2 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 155 !! 155 !! 772 !! 599 !! 173 !! 3.0 !! 26 !! 431 !! 16.6 !! 84 !! 1 !! 87 !! 11 !! 6 !! 61\n|-\n| colspan=\"17\"|Source:<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Devin McCourty Stats|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/13236/devin-mccourty|website=ESPN|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nMcCourty was raised in [[Nyack, New York]], by his parents Phyllis and Calvin McCourty. His father died in 1990 at age 34 due to a heart attack related to complications from [[asthma]]. Devin has a twin brother, Jason McCourty, and an older brother named Larry White. He was born 27 minutes before Jason and they both weighed six pounds and 13 ounces each. During junior high school, the family moved into a mobile home in [[Nanuet, New York]].<ref>{{cite web| title=McCourty twins committed to mom, football, each other| url=https://www.tennessean.com/22376083| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=tennessean.com| date=January 26, 2015}}</ref> His mother worked as a nurse and made sacrifices throughout their childhood to enroll them in private school. In 2010, his mother retired from her career as a nurse at Rockland Psychiatric in [[Orangeburg, New York]]. Jason and Devin made a pact to earn scholarships to relieve the burden of college tuition from his mother. Devin and Jason purchased their mother a home.<ref>{{cite web| title=McCourty would do fine at pick No. 29| url=http://www.espn.com/new-york/nfl/news/story?id=5117015| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=ESPN.com| author=Marchand, Andrew| date=April 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHis twin brother [[Jason McCourty|Jason]] also played cornerback for Rutgers. Jason was drafted in the sixth round of the [[2009 NFL Draft]] by the [[Tennessee Titans]] and previously played for the [[Cleveland Browns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/rutgersfootball/index.ssf/2009/04/devin_mccourty_with_twin_broth.html|title=Devin McCourty, with twin brother Jason no longer by his side, takes leadership role for Rutgers football|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|first=Bridget|last=Wentworth|date=April 9, 2009|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> On March 15, 2018, the [[Cleveland Browns]] traded Jason McCourty to the [[New England Patriots]] along with a [[2018 NFL Draft|2018]] seventh-round pick for New England's [[2018 NFL Draft|2018]] sixth-round pick.<ref>{{cite web|title=Browns trade veteran CB Jason McCourty to Patriots|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000921491/article/browns-trade-veteran-cb-jason-mccourty-to-patriots|author=Sessler, Marc|website=NFL.com|date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> Devin and Jason are one of only 13 sets of twins in NFL history and are one of five active sets of twins to currently play, along with [[Shaquill Griffin]]/[[Shaquem Griffin]], [[Brandon Dixon]]/[[Brian Dixon (American football)|Brian Dixon]], [[Maurkice Pouncey]]/[[Mike Pouncey]], and previous teammates [[Jacob Hollister]]/[[Cody Hollister]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theadvocate.com/sports/saints/13911738-148/saints-are-twinning-with-the|title=Saints are twinning with the Dixon brothers|accessdate=July 2, 2016|work=The Advocate|author=Ted Lewis}}</ref> They were the first set to play in a Super Bowl together, doing so in [[Super Bowl LIII]].\n\nIn 2016, he married his girlfriend Michelle Powell.<ref>{{cite web|title=See what current and former Patriots celebrated Devin McCourty's wedding|url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/05/05/see-what-current-and-former-patriots-celebrated-devin-mccourtys-wedding|website=Patriots.com|accessdate=February 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224114613/http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/05/05/see-what-current-and-former-patriots-celebrated-devin-mccourtys-wedding|archive-date=February 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> On March 11, 2017, the couple had a baby girl named Londyn and on April 29, 2018 they had a baby boy named Brayden.<ref>{{cite web|title=Devin McCourty used his newborn daughter to convince Dont'a Hightower to return to Patriots|url=https://patriotswire.usatoday.com/2017/04/18/devin-mccourty-used-his-newborn-daughter-to-convince-donta-hightower-to-return-to-patriots/|website=Patriots Wire|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fathers' Daze: A Patriots Baby Boom|url=https://www.si.com/mmqb/2017/06/15/themmqb-talking-football-patriots-super-bowl-champs-new-babies-fathers-day-chris-hogan-stephon|website=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}/</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Devin McCourty announces he's expecting second child|url=https://247sports.com/nfl/new-england-patriots/Bolt/New-England-Patriots-safety-Devin-McCourty-announces-hes-expecting-second-child-112197018|website=247 Sports|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDevin and Jason McCourty jointly delivered the 2019 [[Commencement speech|commencement address]] at Rutgers; they also received honorary doctorates from their alma mater.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/rutgersfootball/2019/05/devin-jason-mccourty-tell-rutgers-grads-to-redefine-success-in-commencement-address.html|title=Devin, Jason McCourty tell Rutgers grads to \u2018redefine success\u2019 in commencement address|last=Kratch|first=James|date=2019-05-19|website=nj.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-20}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nIn the aftermath of the 2013 [[Boston Marathon bombings]], McCourty made a pledge to aid recovery efforts with a donation of $100 for every tackle he makes during the 2013 season, and $200 per interception.<ref>http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4742263/mccourty-joins-amendola-in-pledge</ref> The pledge follows a similar offer by former Patriots wide receiver [[Danny Amendola]] ($100 per reception, $200 per dropped pass).\n\nIn January 2018, McCourty along with the [[punk band]] the [[Dropkick Murphys]], joined together in a raffle raising money for the Dropkick Murphys' The Claddagh Fund and McCourty's Embrace the Kids Foundation. The grand prize included a trip and tickets to [[Super Bowl LII]] in which McCourty's Patriots played.<ref>https://lighthouseraffle.org/raffle/mccourty-dropkicks-the-twin-cities/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100427080823/http://www.patriots.com/team/index.cfm?ac=playerbio&bio=34180 New England Patriots bio]\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20110305174131/http://twitter.com/DMcCourty32 Twitter page]\n\n{{New England Patriots roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{2010 NFL Draft}}\n{{PatriotsFirstPick}}\n{{Patriots2010DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XLIX}}\n{{Super Bowl LI}}\n{{Super Bowl LIII}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCourty, Devin}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots players]]\n[[Category:People from Nyack, New York]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Rutgers Scarlet Knights football players]]\n[[Category:Saint Joseph Regional High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name = Devin McCourty\n| image = Devin McCourty.JPG\n| image_size = 200\n| alt =\n| caption = McCourty with the Patriots in 2011\n| number = 32\n| current_team = New England Patriots\n| position = [[Safety (American and Canadian football position)|Free safety]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|8|13|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Nyack, New York]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lbs = 195\n| high_school = [[Saint Joseph Regional High School|Saint Joseph Regional]]<br />([[Montvale, New Jersey]])\n| college = [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]]\n| draftyear = 2010\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 27\n| pastteams =\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2013present)\n|status=Active\n| highlights =\n* 3\u00d7 [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]], [[Super Bowl LI|LI]], [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2011 Pro Bowl|2010]], [[2017 Pro Bowl|2016]])\n* 3\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2010 All-Pro Team|2010]], [[2013 All-Pro Team|2013]], [[2016 All-Pro Team|2016]])\n* First-team All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] (2009)\n| statweek = \n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1 = [[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n| statvalue1 = 772\n| statlabel2 = [[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2 = 3.0\n| statlabel3 = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n| statvalue3 = 11\n| statlabel4 = [[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n| statvalue4 = 6\n| statlabel5 = [[Interceptions]] \n| statvalue5 = 26\n| statlabel6 = [[Touchdown|Total touchdowns]]\n| statvalue6 = 2\n| statlabel7 = [[Pass deflections]]\n| statvalue7 = 87\n| nfl = MCC600258\n| pfr = McCoDe99 \n}}\n'''Devin McCourty''' (born August 13, 1987) is an [[American football]] [[free safety]] for the [[New England Patriots]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]], and was drafted by the Patriots in the first round of the [[2010 NFL Draft]].\n\n==High school career==\nMcCourty attended [[Saint Joseph Regional High School]] in [[Montvale, New Jersey]], with his twin brother, [[Jason McCourty]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/gallery/2012/before_they_were_patriots?pg=16 |title=Before they were Patriots |accessdate=January 27, 2011 |work=The Boston Globe |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120130002206/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/gallery/2012/before_they_were_patriots?pg=16 |archivedate=January 30, 2012 }}.</ref> He played cornerback and [[free safety]] and was an all-league selection in his final two seasons. As a senior, he had 50 tackles and three interceptions.\n\nConsidered a two-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], McCourty only received one scholarship offer, from Rutgers.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Devin-McCourty-28858;_ylt=AtVwcCNAZc0.thHCHZL1vtVDPZB4 Devin McCourty Recruiting Profile]</ref>\n\n==College career==\nMcCourty attended [[Rutgers University]], and played for the [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football]] team beginning in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1.html |title=Devin McCourty College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> After [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]]ing his first season, McCourty appeared in all 13 games as a freshman in 2006 and recorded 38 tackles and two interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1/gamelog/2006/ |title=Devin McCourty 2006 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In 2007, McCourty and his twin brother [[Jason McCourty]] started at cornerback, with Devin compiling 63 tackles, two interceptions, one forced fumble, and three blocked kicks on [[special teams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1/gamelog/2007/ |title=Devin McCourty 2007 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> He was named an All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Conference]] academic selection in his first two seasons.\n\nMcCourty started 13 games at cornerback in his 2008 junior season, picking up 57 tackles, one interception, and a blocked punt.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1/gamelog/2008/ |title=Devin McCourty 2008 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> \nIn his final season at Rutgers in 2009, McCourty started 13 games at cornerback, while still also working on special teams units. He had a career-high 80 tackles and also recorded one interception and 10 pass deflections. He also averaged 25.4 yards on kickoff returns and had a 98-yard kickoff return, third-longest in school history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/devin-mccourty-1/gamelog/2009 |title=Devin McCourty 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> Following the season, he was named to the All-Big East first team.\n\nMcCourty graduated from Rutgers with a bachelor's degree in sociology.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/21/sports/ncaafootball/21rutgers.html?_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Dave | last=Caldwell | title=The McCourty Twins, Divided Between Rutgers and the N.F.L | date=November 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"2\"|Games !! colspan=\"4\"|Tackles !! colspan=\"4\"|Interceptions\n|-\n! G !! GS !! Comb !! Total !! Ast !! Sack !! Int !! Yards !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n! [[2006 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2006]] !! [[2006 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]]\n| 13 || 13 || 38 || 23 || 15 || 0.5 || 2 || 69 || 34.5 || 1 \n|-\n! [[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007]] !! [[2007 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]]\n| 13 || 13 || 63 || 40 || 23 || 0.5 || 2 || 36 || 18.0 || 1\n|- \n! [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]] !! [[2008 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]]\n| 13 || 13 || 57 || 37 || 20 || 0.0 || 1 || 0 || 0.0 || 0\n|- \n! [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]] !! [[2009 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]]\n| 13 || 13 || 80 || 49 || 31 || 0.0 || 1 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 \n|- \n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 52 !! 52 !! 238 !! 149 !! 89 !! 1.0 !! 6 !! 105 !! 17.5 !! 2 \n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nOn August 25, 2009, NFL analyst [[Gil Brandt]] ranked McCourty the fourth best cornerback prospect heading into the 2010 NFL Draft.<ref>{{cite web| title=Senior class of cornerbacks solid heading into 2010 draft| url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d81223ec6/article/senior-class-of-cornerbacks-solid-heading-into-2010-draft| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com| author=Brandt, Gil| date=August 25, 2010}}</ref> He attended the [[NFL Scouting Combine]] and performed all of the combine drills. On March 10, 2010, McCourty attended Rutger's annual pro day, but chose to stand on his combine numbers and only performed positional drills. At the conclusion of the pre-draft process, McCourty was projected to be a first or second round pick by NFL draft experts and scouts.<ref>{{cite web| title=2010 NFL Draft Scouting Report: Devin McCourty| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/348072-2010-nfl-draft-scouting-report-devin-mccourty| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com}}</ref> He was ranked third best cornerback prospect in the draft by [[Sports Illustrated]] and [[ESPN]], was ranked the fourth best cornerback by DraftScout.com, and was ranked the fifth best cornerback in the draft by [[Bleacher Report]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Devon McCourty, DS #3 CB, Rutgers| url=http://draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=75877&draftyear=2010&genpos=CB| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=Draftscour.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Top 10 Cornerbacks in the NFL Draft| url=https://www.si.com/nfl/photos/2010/04/16-0top-10-cornerbacks-in-the-nfl-draft#3| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=si.com| author=Burke, Chris| date=April 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=2010 NFL Draft: Cornerback Rankings| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/348720-2010-nfl-draft-cornerback-rankings| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Nally, Zach| date=February 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=The top 100 players in 2010 NFL draft| url=http://www.thestate.com/sports/college/university-of-south-carolina/usc-football/article18139145.html| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=thestate.com| author=Legwold, Jeff| date=April 18, 2010}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/09000d5d816dd9ca/2010-Combine-workout-Devin-McCourty Devin McCourty's NFL Combine Workout]\n}}\n{{nfl predraft\n| height ft = 5\n| height in = 10\u00be\n| weight = 193\n| dash = 4.48\n| ten split = 1.60\n| twenty split = 2.65\n| shuttle = 4.07\n| cone drill = 6.70\n| vertical = 36\n| broad ft = 10\n| broad in = 6\n| bench = 16\n| wonderlic = \n| arm span = 32\n| hand span = 9\n| note = All values from [[NFL Combine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/devin-mccourty?id=494287|title=Devin McCourty Combine Profile|work=NFL.com|accessdate=April 10, 2010}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=75877&draftyear=2010&genpos=CB|title=Devin McCourty Draft Profile|work=NFLDraftScout.com|accessdate=April 10, 2010}}.</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010===\nThe [[New England Patriots]] selected McCourty in the first round (27th overall) of the [[2010 NFL Draft]]. He was the third cornerback drafted in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2010/draft.htm |title=2010 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> \n{{external media\n| video1 = [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=o4AfuWmOkAw Patriots draft McCourty 27th overall]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-videos/09000d5d8177f4c3/comments/2010-Draft-Vignettes-Devin-McCourty-Rutgers 2010 NFL Draft Vignette: Devin McCourty]\n}}\nOn July 28, 2010, the New England Patriots signed McCourty to a five-year, [[United States dollar|$]]10 million contract that includes $7.28 million guaranteed and a [[signing bonus]] of $1.50 million.<ref>{{cite web| title=Contract Details on Devin McCourty| url=https://www.patspulpit.com/2010/7/28/1592046/contract-details-on-devin-mccourty| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=patspulpit.com| author=Knopping, Greg| date=July 28, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/nfl/news/story?id=5416241|title=Devin McCourty agrees to deal|work=ESPNBoston.com|first=Mike|last=Reiss|date=July 28, 2010|accessdate=July 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"spotrac\">{{cite web| title=Spotrac.com: Devin McCourty contract| url=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/new-england-patriots/devin-mccourty-6536/| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=Spotrac.com}}</ref>\n\nUpon him arriving in training camp, McCourty began competing for a job as a starting cornerback against [[Darius Butler]]. Head coach [[Bill Belichick]] named both McCourty and Darius Butler the starting cornerbacks to begin the regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 09/06/2010| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/111/NE| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| \ntitle=PATRIOTS FOOTBALL: Starting CB Bodden placed on IR| url=https://www.middletownpress.com/news/article/PATRIOTS-FOOTBALL-Starting-CB-Bodden-placed-on-IR-11879131.php| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=middletownpress.com| author=Associated Press| date=August 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe made his professional regular season debut and first career start in the [[2010 New England Patriots|New England Patriots']] season-opener against the [[2010 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]] and recorded five solo tackles and a pass deflection in their 38\u201324 victory.<ref name=\"stats10\"/> McCourty made his first career tackle on [[Adam Jones (American football)|Adam Jones]], ending Jones 19-yard kick return in the first quarter.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 1-2010: Cincinnati Bengals @ New England Patriots| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2010091202/2010/REG1/bengals@patriots#tab=recap| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> On October 24, 2010, McCourty made three combined tackles, a pass deflection, and made his first career interception off a pass by quarterback [[Philip Rivers]] during a 23\u201320 win at the [[2010 San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] in Week 7.<ref name=\"stats10\"/> McCourty intercepted the pass that was originally intended for [[Patrick Crayton]] in the second quarter and was immediately tackled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201010240sdg.htm |title=New England Patriots at San Diego Chargers - October 24th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On November 14, 2010, he collected a season-high 11 combined tackles (nine solo) and broke up a pass in the Patriots' 39\u201326 victory at the [[2010 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh]] in Week 10.<ref name=\"stats10\"/> In Week 11, he collected six combined tackles, two pass deflections, and an interception in the Patriots' 31\u201328 win against the [[2010 Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref name=\"stats10\"/> The following week, McCourty made a season-high three pass deflections, seven combined tackles, and intercepted two passes by [[Matthew Stafford]] in a 45\u201324 victory at the [[2010 Detroit Lions|Detroit Lions]] in Week 12. The feat marked his first multi-interception game of his career.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201011250det.htm |title=New England Patriots at Detroit Lions - November 25th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On December 6, 2010, McCourty recorded three solo tackles, broke up a pass, and an interception as the Patriots routed the [[2010 New York Jets|New York Jets]] 45\u20133 in Week 13.<ref name=\"stats10\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2010)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2010| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> The interception was his sixth pick of the season and continued his three-game streak with an interception. In Week 15, he collected ten solo tackles (seven solo), a pass deflection, and made his first career sack on quarterback [[Aaron Rodgers|Matt Flynn]] during a 31\u201327 win against the [[2010 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012190nwe.htm |title=Green Bay Packers at New England Patriots - December 19th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On December 29, 2010, it was announced that McCourty was voted to the [[2011 Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web| title=2011 Pro Bowl: Tom Brady, Vince Wilfork, Devin McCourty Headline Patriots| url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2010/12/29/1901911/2011-pro-bowl-tom-brady-vince-wilfork-devin-mccourty-patriots| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=SBNation.com| author=Thorman, Joel| date=December 29, 2010}}</ref> He finished his rookie season in 2010 with 82 combined tackles (69 solo), 17 pass deflections, seven interceptions, two forced fumbles, and a sack in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref name=\"career\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (career)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/careerstats| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> His 17 pass deflections and seven interceptions marked career-highs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/Players/M/McCoDe99/gamelog/2010/ |title=Devin McCourty 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> McCourty was named a First-Team [[All-Pro]] by the [[Sporting News]] and Second-Team All-Pro by [[The Associated Press]].\n\nThe New England Patriots finished first in the [[AFC East]] with a 14\u20132 record and clinched home-field advantage and a first round bye. On January 16, 2011, McCourty started in his first career playoff game and collected three solo tackles in their 28\u201321 loss to the [[2010 New York Jets|New York Jets]] in the AFC Divisional Round.<ref name=\"stats10\"/> On January 30, 2011, he appeared in the 2011 Pro Bowl and recorded four solo tackles, two pass deflections, and intercepted a pass by [[Michael Vick]]. He was part of Bill Belichick's AFC team that lost 55\u201341 to the NFC.<ref name=\"stats10\"/>\n\n===2011===\nMcCourty entered training camp slated as the Patriots' No. 1 starting cornerback.<ref>{{cite web| title=Devin McCourty and Leigh Bodden, New England Patriots' Super Bowl Caliber CBs | url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/800577-devin-mccourty-and-leigh-bodden-new-england-patriots-super-bowl-caliber-cbs| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Dimaio, James| date=August 12, 2011}}</ref> Head coach Bill Belichick officially named McCourty the starter, alongside Leigh Bodden, to start the regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 09/04/2011| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/123/NE| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> On September 8, 2011, it was reported that McCourty was selected by teammates to be one of the six team captains. McCourty, [[Jerod Mayo]], and [[Vince Wilfork]] were chosen to be defensive captains for the season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Report: Patriots Name 2011 Captains| url=https://www.patspulpit.com/platform/2011/9/8/2412383/report-patriots-name-2011-captains| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=patspulpit.com| author=Knopping, Greg| date=September 8, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nMcCourty started in [[2011 New England Patriots|New England Patriots']] season-opener at the [[2011 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]] and collected a season-high 11 combined tackles (ten solo) and two pass deflections in their 38\u201324 victory. On November 13, 2011, he made four solo tackles during 37\u201316 victory at the [[2011 New York Jets|New York Jets]], but exited in the second quarter after injuring his shoulder during a collision with teammate [[Sterling Moore]]. His shoulder injury sidelined him for the next two games (Weeks 11\u201312).<ref>{{cite web| title=Devin McCourty suffers shoulder injury| url=http://www.espn.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/7232153/new-england-patriots-devin-mccourty-injures-shoulder-new-york-jets| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=ESPN.com| date=November 14, 2011}}</ref> In Week 16, McCourty collected nine combined tackles, a season-high five pass deflections, and made an interception during a 27\u201324 victory. He finished the {{NFL Year|2011}} season with 87 combined tackles (65 solo), 13 pass deflections, and two interceptions in 14 games and 14 starts.<ref name=\"career\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McCoDe99/gamelog/2011/ |title=Devin McCourty 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe New England Patriots finished first in the AFC East with a 13\u20133 record. They went on to defeat the [[2011 Denver Broncos|Denver Broncos]] 45\u201310 in the AFC Divisional Round and the [[2011 Baltimore Ravens|Baltimore Ravens]] 23\u201320 in the AFC Championship to advance to the Super Bowl. On February 5, 2012, McCourty started in [[Super Bowl XLVI]] and collected seven combined tackles as the Patriots lost to the [[New York Giants]] by a score of 21\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201202050nwe.htm |title=Super Bowl XLVI - New York Giants vs. New England Patriots - February 5th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\nMcCourty entered training camp slated as the No. 1 starting cornerback.<ref>{{cite web| title=Analyzing 2012 Patriots Roster| url=http://www.espn.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4721463/analyzing-2012-patriots-roster| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=ESPN.com| author=Rodak, Mike| date=April 30, 2012}}</ref> Defensive coordinator [[Matt Patricia]] named McCourty and [[Kyle Arrington]] the starting cornerbacks to start the season, ahead of [[Ras-I Dowling]], [[Will Allen (cornerback)|Will Allen]], [[Sterling Moore]], and [[Alfonzo Dennard]]. He was also named the starting kick returner by special teams coordinator [[Scott O'Brien]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 10/01/2012| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/136/NE| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> On September 6, 2012, it was announced that McCourty was selected to be a captain for the second consecutive season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots Name Six 2012 Team Captains| url=https://www.boston.cbslocal.com/2012/09/06/patriots-name-six-2012-team-captains/| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=boston.cbslocal.com| date=September 6, 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502165534/http://boston.cbslocal.com/2012/09/06/patriots-name-six-2012-team-captains/| archive-date=May 2, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 4, McCourty collected four solo tackles, two pass deflections, and intercepted two passes by quarterback [[Ryan Fitzpatrick]] during a 52\u201328 win at the [[2012 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 4-2012: New England Patriots @ Buffalo Bills| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2012093000/2012/REG4/patriots@bills| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> On October 21, 2012, McCourty made five solo tackles and returned a kick for a touchdown during a 29\u201326 overtime win against the [[2012 New York Jets|New York Jets]] in Week 7.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201210210nwe.htm |title=New York Jets at New England Patriots - October 21st, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> His kick return was for 104-yards and occurred in the first quarter. It became his first and only career kick return for a touchdown.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week7-2012: New York Jets @ Denver Broncos| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2012102108/2012/REG7/jets@patriots| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> His performance in Week 7 earned him AFC Special Teams Player of the Week. On November 1, 2012, the New England Patriots acquired cornerback [[Aqib Talib]] in a trade with the [[2012 Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000089499/article/new-england-patriots-move-devin-mccourty-to-safety|title=New England Patriots move Devin McCourty to safety|work=[[National Football League]]|date=November 4, 2012|accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref> Following the trade, it was reported that McCourty would be moving to free safety after struggling at cornerback during the first eight games.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots moving struggling DB McCourty to safety| url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2012/11/08/patriots-devin-mccourty-safety-ap| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=SI.com| date=November 8, 2012}}</ref> His move to safety was also attributed to injuries to safeties [[Steve Gregory (football player)|Steve Gregory]] and [[Patrick Chung]] and the emergence of Kyle Arrington and Alfonzo Dennard as productive cornerbacks.<ref>{{cite web| title=In new role, Devin McCourty provides a safety net| url=https://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2012/11/07/in-new-role-devin-mccourty-provides-a-safety-net| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=Boston.com| author=Whitmer, Michael| date=November 7, 2012}}</ref> McCourty immediately assumed the job as the starting free safety, replacing Patrick Chung, who was still recovering from a shoulder injury.<ref>{{cite web| title=Hernandez, Chung Out; 11 Questionable For Patriots Vs. Rams| url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2012/10/26/hernanez-chung-out-11-questionable-for-patriots-vs-rams/| accessdate=April 25, 2018| website=boston.cbslocal.com| date=October 26, 2012}}/</ref> On November 11, 2012, he made his debut as the starting free safety and recorded eight combined tackles, a pass deflection, and an interception in the Patriots' 37\u201331 win against the [[2012 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]] in Week 10.<ref name=\"stats12\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2012)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2012| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=April 27, 2018}}</ref> McCourty finished the {{NFL Year|2012}} season with 82 combined tackles (63 solo), 13 pass deflections, five interceptions, two forced fumbles, and a touchdown in 16 games and 16 starts. He started the last eight games at free safety and also served as the kick returner throughout the season. McCourty finished with 24 kick returns for a total of 654-yards and one touchdown.<ref name=\"career\"/> McCourty played a total of 1,329 snaps on defense and special teams. His snap total finished third in the league in 2012, behind teammates [[Ryan Wendell]] and [[Nate Solder]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.footballoutsiders.com/stats/snapcounts2012 |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203051518/http://www.footballoutsiders.com/stats/snapcounts2012 |archive-date=December 3, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[2012 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] completed the regular season in first place in the AFC East with a 12\u20134 record. On January 13, 2013, McCourty made his first postseason start at safety and collected eight combined tackles during a 41\u201328 win against the [[2012 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]] in the AFC Divisional Round.<ref name=\"stats12\"/> The following week, he made eight combined tackles as the Patriots were eliminated from the playoffs after a 28\u201313 loss to the [[2012 Baltimore Ravens|Baltimore Ravens]] in the AFC Championship Game.<ref name=\"stats12\"/>\n\n===2013===\nMcCourty began training camp as the ''de facto'' starting free safety after Patrick Chung departed in [[free agency (sports)|free agency]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Full Training Camp Roster Breakdown for Patriots| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1682910-full-training-camp-roster-breakdown-for-patriots| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Dessault, Mike| date=July 18, 2013}}</ref> He was named the starting free safety to open the regular season, alongside strong safety [[Steve Gregory]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 09/05/2013| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/150/NE| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> \nMcCourty was not selected as one of four team captains to begin the regular season. He became a captain, along with [[Rob Ninkovich]], mid-season after injuries to Mayo and Wilfork.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots Announce Team Captains: Dan Connolly the newest addition| url=https://www.patspulpit.com/platform/2014/9/3/6101251/patriots-announce-team-captains-dan-connolly-the-newest-addition| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=patspulpit.com| author=Knopping, Greg| date=September 3, 2014}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, 2013, McCourty collected a season-high 12 combined tackles (eight solo) during a 13\u20136 loss at the [[2013 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]] in Week 5.<ref name=\"stats13\"/> In Week 9, he made six combined tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass by [[Ben Roethlisberger]] in the Patriots' 55\u201331 win against the [[2013 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref name=\"stats13\"/> He was inactive for the Patriots' Week 17 victory against the [[2013 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]] after head coach Bill Belichick chose to rest him for the playoffs.<ref name=\"stats13\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2013)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2013| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> McCourty finished the season with 69 combined tackles (48 solo), nine pass deflections, and an interception in 15 games and 15 starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McCoDe99/gamelog/2013 |title=Devin McCourty 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref> He received the highest overall grade among all qualified safeties in 2013.<ref name=\"PFF\">{{cite web| title=Patriots Re-sign Devin McCourty| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/news/patriots-re-sign-devin-mccourty| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nMcCourty began the regular season as the starting free safety and played alongside strong safety Patrick Chung.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots Depth Chart: 10/01/2014| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/164/NE| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> This began a five-year stint where McCourty and Chung were the main starting safeties for the Patriots.\n\nIn Week 2, McCourty deflected a pass and also returned an interception for a 60-yard gain before being pushed out of bounds at the goal line during a 30\u20137 win at the [[2014 Minnesota Vikings|Minnesota Vikings]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409140min.htm |title=New England Patriots at Minnesota Vikings - September 14th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On November 30, 2014, McCourty collected a season-high nine combined tackles (eight solo) in the Patriots' 26\u201321 loss at the [[2014 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]] in Week 13.<ref name=\"stats14\"/> He finished the season with 68 combined tackles (51 solo), six pass deflections, two interceptions, and a forced fumble in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref name=\"career\"/> He earned the eighth highest overall grade from Pro Football Focus in 2015.<ref name=\"PFF\"/>\n\nThe [[2015 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] finished atop the AFC East with a 12\u20134 record, clinching a first round bye and home-field advantage. On January 10, 2015, he made four combined tackles, two pass deflections, and intercepted a pass by [[Joe Flacco]] during a 35-31 victory against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens|Baltimore Ravens]] in the AFC Divisional Round.<ref name=\"stats14\"/> The Patriots reached Super Bowl XLIX after routing the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis Colts]] 45\u20137 in the AFC Championship Game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501100nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots - January 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On February 1, 2015, McCourty collected five combined tackles and helped the Patriots defeat the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks|Seattle Seahawks]] 28\u201324 and win [[Super Bowl XLIX]].<ref name=\"stats14\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2014)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2014| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nMcCourty became an unrestricted free agent in 2015 and received interest from multiple teams, including the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], [[New York Giants]], [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], and [[Tennessee Titans]].<ref name=\"PFF\"/>\n\nOn March 9, 2015, the New England Patriots signed McCourty to a five-year, $47.5 million contract with $28.5 million guaranteed and a signing bonus of $15 million.<ref name=\"spotrac\"/><ref>http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/12446830/safety-devin-mccourty-re-sign-new-england-patriots-according-report</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4778888/breaking-down-devin-mccourtys-contract|title = Breaking down Devin McCourty's contract|last = Yates|first = Field|date = March 9, 2015|work = |access-date = March 9, 2015|publisher = ESPNBoston.com}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 6, McCourty collected a season-high nine combined tackles during a 34\u201327 win at the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis Colts]]. On October 29, 2015, he made four solo tackles and sacked quarterback [[Ryan Tannehill]] in New England's 36\u20137 win against the [[2015 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]] in Week 8. The sack became only the second one of his career and was his first sack since his rookie season.<ref name=\"stats15\"/> On December 13, 2015, McCourty made one tackle before exiting the Patriots' 27\u20136 victory at the [[2015 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]] in the second quarter due to an ankle injury.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots safety Devin McCourty leaves game with ankle injury| url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2015/12/13/devin-mccourty-injury-update-ankle-patriots| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=SI.com}}</ref> His injury sidelined him for the next two games (Weeks 15\u201316). He registered 64 combined tackles (51 solo), six passes defensed, one sack, and an interception in 14 games and 14 starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McCoDe99/gamelog/2015 |title=Devin McCourty 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The Patriots began deploying [[Duron Harmon]] in a three-safety technique at the end of the season.\n\nThe [[2015 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] finished atop their division with a 12\u20134 record. They defeated the [[2015 Kansas City Chiefs|Kansas City Chiefs]] in the AFC Divisional Round, before losing to the eventual [[Super Bowl 50|Super Bowl 50 Champions]], the [[2015 Denver Broncos|Denver Broncos]], in the AFC Championship Game.<ref name=\"stats15\"/> McCourty made seven combined tackles and two pass deflections throughout the playoffs with only two tackles and one deflection against the Broncos.<ref name=\"stats15\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2015)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2015| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn September 6, 2016, the New England Patriots announced the selection of McCourty as one of four team captains to start the regular season. It was his third consecutive selection and fifth overall.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots 2016 team captains include Rob Gronkowski, Dont\u2019a Hightower, but not Tom Brady|url=http://www.patspulpit.com/2016/9/6/12822914/patriots-announce-team-captains-2016-including-rob-gronkowski-donta-hightower-slater-brady-mccourty|author=Hill, Rich|website=PatsPulpit.com|date=September 6, 2016|accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe started in the [[2016 New England Patriots|New England Patriots']] season-opener at the [[2016 Arizona Cardinals|Arizona Cardinals]] and recorded a season-high ten combined tackles (nine solo) in their 23\u201321 victory. On December 12, 2016, McCourty made four solo tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass by [[Joe Flacco]] during a 30\u201323 win against the [[2016 Baltimore Ravens|Baltimore Ravens]] in Week 14.<ref name=\"stats16\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2016)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2016| accessdate=April 26, 2018| website=NFL.com}}/</ref> On December 20, McCourty was named to the [[2017 Pro Bowl]], his second time receiving the honor. He finished the season with 83 combined tackles (67 solo), seven pass deflections, an interception, and a forced fumble in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref name=\"career\"/> At the end of the season he was named second-team [[2016 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Three rookies, Matt Ryan among players named to All-Pro team|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000770458/article/three-rookies-matt-ryan-among-players-named-to-allpro-team?campaign=Twitter_atn|website=NFL.com|date=January 6, 2017}}</ref> He played 1022 defensive snaps (98%).<ref>{{cite web| title=Pro-Football Reference: New England Patriots Snap Count (2016)| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2016-snap-counts.htm| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=pro-football-reference.com}}</ref> He received an overall grade of 89.6 from Pro Football Focus and had the fourth highest grade among all qualified safeties in 2016. He also earned a coverage grade of 91.9.<ref>{{cite web| title=Safety Devin McCourty remains key to Patriots' defense| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/news/pro-devin-mccourty-remains-key-to-patriots-defense| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com| author=Gellar, Cyrus| date=May 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2016 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] finished first in their division with a 14\u20132 record and earned home-field advantage.<ref name=\"stats16\"/> On January 14, 2017, McCourty made five combined tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass during a 34\u201316 victory against the [[2016 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]] in the AFC Divisional Round.<ref name=\"stats16\"/> The Patriots went on to Super Bowl LI after defeating the [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]] 36\u201317 in the AFC Championship Game.<ref name=\"stats16\"/> On February 5, 2017, McCourty started in [[Super Bowl LI]] and made five combined tackles as the Patriots defeated the [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] 34\u201328 in overtime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm|title=Super Bowl LI - New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons - February 5th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=September 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2017020500/2016/POST22/patriots@falcons#menu=gameinfo%7CcontentId%3A0ap3000000783776&tab=analyze&analyze=boxscore|title=Watch New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons [02/05/2017]|work=NFL.com|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm|title=Super Bowl LI - New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons - February 5th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n[[File:Super Bowl 1F2868F4.jpg|thumb|McCourty in [[Super Bowl LII]]]]\nMcCourty and Patrick Chung remained the starting safety duo with [[Duron Harmon]] acting as the third safety to begin the regular season. In Week 5, he collected a season-high 11 solo tackles during a 19\u201314 victory at the [[2017 Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref name=\"stats17\"/> The following week, he made five combined tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass by [[Josh McCown]] in the Patriots' 24\u201317 victory at the [[2017 New York Jets|New York Jets]] in Week 6.<ref name=\"stats17\"/> On December 11, 2017, McCourty collected seven solo tackles and sacked quarterback [[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]] during a 27\u201320 loss at the [[2017 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]]. The sack became his third of his career.<ref name=\"stats17\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Devin McCourty (2017)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinmccourty/494287/gamelogs?season=2017| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> McCourty finished the season with a career-high 97 combined tackles (80 solo), five pass deflections, an interception, and a sack in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref name=\"career\"/> [[Pro Football Focus]] gave McCourty an overall grade of 82.6, ranking 23rd among all qualified safeties in 2017.<ref>{{cite web| title=Pro Football Focus: Devin McCourty| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/nfl/players/devin-mccourty/5552| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2017 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] finished first in the AFC East with a 13\u20133 record and received a first round bye and home-field advantage. They defeated the [[2017 Tennessee Titans|Tennessee Titans]] in the AFC Divisional Round and the [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars|Jacksonville Jaguars]] in the AFC Championship Game.<ref name=\"stats17\"/> On February 4, 2018, McCourty started in [[Super Bowl LII]] and collected seven combined tackles and two pass deflections in the Patriots' 41\u201333 loss to the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles|Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref name=\"stats17\"/>\n\n===2018===\nIn the preseason, Devin McCourty was reunited with his brother [[Jason McCourty]], who played as cornerback for the [[Tennessee Titans]] and the winless [[Cleveland Browns]] in 2017. Jason started as the number two cornerback in New England's secondary and formed a strong duo with All-Pro corner [[Stephon Gilmore]].\n\nIn Week 8 against the [[Buffalo Bills]], McCourty had an 84 yard pick six off [[Derek Anderson (American football)|Derek Anderson]] as the Patriots won the game 25-6. McCourty helped the Patriots win [[Super Bowl LIII]]. Overall in 2018 Mccourty had 1 interception for 23 yards and 82 tackles\n\n===2019===\nIn Week 1 against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], McCourty made his first interception of the season off [[Ben Roethlisberger]] in the endzone during the 33-3 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127860 |title=Brady starts his 20th season by beating Steelers 33-3 |date=8 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref> In Week 2 against the [[Miami Dolphins]], McCourty had his second interception of the season off of [[Ryan Fitzpatrick]] in the 43-0 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2019091505/2019/REG2/patriots@dolphins?icampaign=scoreStrip-globalNav-2019091505}}</ref>\nIn Week 3 against the [[New York Jets]], McCourty recorded his third interception of the season off [[Luke Falk]] in the 30-14 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127861 |title=Brady, Patriots defense shine in 30-14 win over Jets |date=22 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\nIn Week 4 against the [[Buffalo Bills]], McCourty intercepted his fourth pass of the season off [[Josh Allen (quarterback)|Josh Allen]] in the 16-10 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127866 |title=Patriots stay undefeated, hang on to beat Bills 16-10|date=29 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\nMcCourty became the first player to record 4 interceptions in a season's first 4 games since [[Minnesota Vikings]]' safety [[Brian Russell]] accomplished this feat in the 2003 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/devin-on-the-spot-patriots-mc-courty-now-has-four-interceptions-in-the-seasons-four-games-175146931.html |title=Devin on the spot: Patriots' McCourty now has four interceptions in the season's four games |last=Young |first=Shalise |date=29 September 2019 |website=www.sports.yahoo.com |access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> He was named AFC Defensive Player of the Month for September.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Buchmasser |first1=Bernd |title=Patriots safety Devin McCourty is the AFC Defensive Player of the Month for September |url=https://www.patspulpit.com/2019/10/3/20896743/new-england-patriots-safety-devin-mccourty-afc-defensive-player-of-the-month-september |website=PatsPulpit.com |publisher=Pats Pulpit |accessdate=October 3, 2019|date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 7 against the [[New York Jets]], McCourty recorded his fifth interception of the season off [[Sam Darnold]] in the 33-0 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127894 |title=Patriots blitz Darnold, Jets 33-0 to remain undefeated |date=20 October 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 8 against the [[Cleveland Browns]], McCourty recovered a fumble forced by teammate [[Jonathan Jones (American football)|Jonathan Jones]] on [[Nick Chubb]] in the 27-13 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127895 |title=Belichick wins 300th, perfect Patriots beat Browns 27-13 |date=27 October 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 14 against the [[Kansas City Chiefs]], McCourty forced a fumble on tight end [[Travis Kelce]] which was recovered by teammate [[Stephon Gilmore]] during the 23\u201316 loss. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127930 |title=KC survives mistakes, take AFC West with 23-13 win over Pats |date=December 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nOn March 17, 2020, McCourty signed a two-year, $23 million contract extension to stay with the Patriots.<ref>{{cite web|work=Patriots.com|url=https://www.patriots.com/news/report-devin-mccourty-signs-two-year-extension-with-patriots|date=March 15, 2020|title=Report: Devin McCourty signs two-year extension with Patriots|first=Mike|last=Dussault|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL career statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n| [[List of Super Bowl champions|Won the Super Bowl]]\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"2\"|Games !! colspan=\"4\"|Tackles !! colspan=\"6\"|Interceptions !! colspan=\"3\"|Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Comb !! Solo !! Ast !! Sack!! Int !! Yar