 772 !! 599 !! 173 !! 3.0 !! 26 !! 431 !! 16.6 !! 84 !! 1 !! 87 !! 11 !! 6 !! 61\n|-\n| colspan=\"17\"|Source:<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Devin McCourty Stats|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/13236/devin-mccourty|website=ESPN|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nMcCourty was raised in [[Nyack, New York]], by his parents Phyllis and Calvin McCourty. His father died in 1990 at age 34 due to a heart attack related to complications from [[asthma]]. Devin has a twin brother, Jason McCourty, and an older brother named Larry White. He was born 27 minutes before Jason and they both weighed six pounds and 13 ounces each. During junior high school, the family moved into a mobile home in [[Nanuet, New York]].<ref>{{cite web| title=McCourty twins committed to mom, football, each other| url=https://www.tennessean.com/22376083| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=tennessean.com| date=January 26, 2015}}</ref> His mother worked as a nurse and made sacrifices throughout their childhood to enroll them in private school. In 2010, his mother retired from her career as a nurse at Rockland Psychiatric in [[Orangeburg, New York]]. Jason and Devin made a pact to earn scholarships to relieve the burden of college tuition from his mother. Devin and Jason purchased their mother a home.<ref>{{cite web| title=McCourty would do fine at pick No. 29| url=http://www.espn.com/new-york/nfl/news/story?id=5117015| accessdate=April 27, 2018| website=ESPN.com| author=Marchand, Andrew| date=April 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHis twin brother [[Jason McCourty|Jason]] also played cornerback for Rutgers. Jason was drafted in the sixth round of the [[2009 NFL Draft]] by the [[Tennessee Titans]] and previously played for the [[Cleveland Browns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/rutgersfootball/index.ssf/2009/04/devin_mccourty_with_twin_broth.html|title=Devin McCourty, with twin brother Jason no longer by his side, takes leadership role for Rutgers football|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|first=Bridget|last=Wentworth|date=April 9, 2009|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> On March 15, 2018, the [[Cleveland Browns]] traded Jason McCourty to the [[New England Patriots]] along with a [[2018 NFL Draft|2018]] seventh-round pick for New England's [[2018 NFL Draft|2018]] sixth-round pick.<ref>{{cite web|title=Browns trade veteran CB Jason McCourty to Patriots|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000921491/article/browns-trade-veteran-cb-jason-mccourty-to-patriots|author=Sessler, Marc|website=NFL.com|date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> Devin and Jason are one of only 13 sets of twins in NFL history and are one of five active sets of twins to currently play, along with [[Shaquill Griffin]]/[[Shaquem Griffin]], [[Brandon Dixon]]/[[Brian Dixon (American football)|Brian Dixon]], [[Maurkice Pouncey]]/[[Mike Pouncey]], and previous teammates [[Jacob Hollister]]/[[Cody Hollister]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theadvocate.com/sports/saints/13911738-148/saints-are-twinning-with-the|title=Saints are twinning with the Dixon brothers|accessdate=July 2, 2016|work=The Advocate|author=Ted Lewis}}</ref> They were the first set to play in a Super Bowl together, doing so in [[Super Bowl LIII]].\n\nIn 2016, he married his girlfriend Michelle Powell.<ref>{{cite web|title=See what current and former Patriots celebrated Devin McCourty's wedding|url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/05/05/see-what-current-and-former-patriots-celebrated-devin-mccourtys-wedding|website=Patriots.com|accessdate=February 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224114613/http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/05/05/see-what-current-and-former-patriots-celebrated-devin-mccourtys-wedding|archive-date=February 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> On March 11, 2017, the couple had a baby girl named Londyn and on April 29, 2018 they had a baby boy named Brayden.<ref>{{cite web|title=Devin McCourty used his newborn daughter to convince Dont'a Hightower to return to Patriots|url=https://patriotswire.usatoday.com/2017/04/18/devin-mccourty-used-his-newborn-daughter-to-convince-donta-hightower-to-return-to-patriots/|website=Patriots Wire|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fathers' Daze: A Patriots Baby Boom|url=https://www.si.com/mmqb/2017/06/15/themmqb-talking-football-patriots-super-bowl-champs-new-babies-fathers-day-chris-hogan-stephon|website=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}/</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Devin McCourty announces he's expecting second child|url=https://247sports.com/nfl/new-england-patriots/Bolt/New-England-Patriots-safety-Devin-McCourty-announces-hes-expecting-second-child-112197018|website=247 Sports|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDevin and Jason McCourty jointly delivered the 2019 [[Commencement speech|commencement address]] at Rutgers; they also received honorary doctorates from their alma mater.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/rutgersfootball/2019/05/devin-jason-mccourty-tell-rutgers-grads-to-redefine-success-in-commencement-address.html|title=Devin, Jason McCourty tell Rutgers grads to \u2018redefine success\u2019 in commencement address|last=Kratch|first=James|date=2019-05-19|website=nj.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-20}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nIn the aftermath of the 2013 [[Boston Marathon bombings]], McCourty made a pledge to aid recovery efforts with a donation of $100 for every tackle he makes during the 2013 season, and $200 per interception.<ref>http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4742263/mccourty-joins-amendola-in-pledge</ref> The pledge follows a similar offer by former Patriots wide receiver [[Danny Amendola]] ($100 per reception, $200 per dropped pass).\n\nIn January 2018, McCourty along with the [[punk band]] the [[Dropkick Murphys]], joined together in a raffle raising money for the Dropkick Murphys' The Claddagh Fund and McCourty's Embrace the Kids Foundation. The grand prize included a trip and tickets to [[Super Bowl LII]] in which McCourty's Patriots played.<ref>https://lighthouseraffle.org/raffle/mccourty-dropkicks-the-twin-cities/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100427080823/http://www.patriots.com/team/index.cfm?ac=playerbio&bio=34180 New England Patriots bio]\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20110305174131/http://twitter.com/DMcCourty32 Twitter page]\n\n{{New England Patriots roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{2010 NFL Draft}}\n{{PatriotsFirstPick}}\n{{Patriots2010DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XLIX}}\n{{Super Bowl LI}}\n{{Super Bowl LIII}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCourty, Devin}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots players]]\n[[Category:People from Nyack, New York]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Rutgers Scarlet Knights football players]]\n[[Category:Saint Joseph Regional High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n", "name_user": "71.115.227.65", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200e2017)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Devin_McCourty"}
{"title_page": "Mike Homik", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Mike Homik\n| image = \n| caption = \n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_cm = 204\n| weight_kg = 115\n| league = \n| team = \n| number = \n| nationality = New Zealand\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|7|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n| high_school = [[St John's College, Hamilton|St John's College]]<br>(Hamilton, New Zealand)\n| college = [[West Valley College|West Valley JC]] (1997\u20131999)<br>[[College of Idaho]] (2000\u20132002)\n| career_start = 1996\n| career_end = 2015\n| years1 = 1996\u20131997\n| team1 = [[Waikato Pistons|Waikato Warriors]]\n| years2 = 2003\u20132005\n| team2 = [[Auckland Stars]]\n| years3 = 2003\u20132004\n| team3 = [[New Zealand Breakers]]\n| years4 = 2006\n| team4 = [[Harbour Heat]]\n| years5 = 2007\u20132010\n| team5 = [[Waikato Pistons]]\n| years6 = 2007\u20132008\n| team6 = [[Perth Wildcats]]\n| years7 = 2011\u20132012\n| team7 = [[Manawatu Jets]]\n| years8 = 2013\n| team8 = [[Wellington Saints]]\n| years9 = 2015\n| team9 = Manawatu Jets\n| highlights =\n*4\u00d7 [[List of New Zealand NBL champions|NZNBL champion]] (2004, 2005, 2008, 2009)\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{NZL}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2006 Commonwealth Games|2006 Melbourne]] | Team Competition}}\n}}\n'''Michael Homik''' (born 6 July 1978) is a New Zealand former [[basketball]] player. He played 14 seasons in the [[National Basketball League (New Zealand)|National Basketball League]] (NBL) and won four [[List of New Zealand NBL champions|championships]]. He also played for the [[New Zealand national basketball team|Tall Blacks]] and won a silver medal at the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]].\n\n==Early life==\nHomik was born and raised in [[Hamilton, New Zealand]], where he attended [[St John's College, Hamilton|St John's College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/2920515/Head-and-shoulders-above-rest |title=Head and shoulders above rest |first=Daniel |last=Richardson |work=Stuff.co.nz |publisher=Fairfax Media |date=1 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tyugts8h?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/2920515/Head-and-shoulders-above-rest |archivedate=4 November 2010 |accessdate=4 November 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=retire>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/7023398/Jets-lose-retired-Homik-as-stunt-job-beckons Jets lose retired Homik as stunt job beckons]</ref>\n\n==Basketball career==\nIn 1996, Homik debuted in the NBL for the [[Waikato Pistons|Waikato Warriors]].<ref name=bbnz>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060824051930/http://www.basketball.org.nz/index.cgi?sID=43&intArticleID=674&det=1 Mike Homik Basketball NZ profile]</ref> He played seven games in both 1996 and 1997, before moving to the United States for college.<ref name=\"bbnz\" /> He played two seasons of [[college basketball]] for [[West Valley College]] before transferring to [[College of Idaho|Albertson College of Idaho]].\n\nHomik returned from the United States in 2003 and joined the [[Auckland Stars]].<ref>[http://www.olympic.org.nz/athletes/michael-homik/ Michael Homik NZ Olympic profile]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nzgirl.co.nz/know/2253/ |title=2003 NBL Teams and Draw |access-date=18 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907144718/http://www.nzgirl.co.nz/know/2253/ |archive-date=7 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He later joined the [[New Zealand Breakers]] for their inaugural season in the [[National Basketball League (Australia)|Australian NBL]] in [[2003\u201304 NBL season|2003/04]]. In 2004 and 2005, he was a member of the Stars' back-to-back championship teams.\n\nFor the [[2006 New Zealand NBL season]], Homik played for the [[Harbour Heat]]. He went on to spend the next four NBL seasons playing for the [[Waikato Pistons]], including winning championships in 2008 and 2009. During this time, he played a second season in the Australian NBL, this time with the [[Perth Wildcats]] in [[2007\u201308 NBL season|2007/08]].<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/Sport/NBL-preseason-close-to-tipoff/2007/07/27/1185339243592.html NBL pre-season close to tip-off]</ref>\n\nFor the [[2011 New Zealand NBL season]], Homik joined the [[Manawatu Jets]].<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/basketball/4434739/Jets-stronger-as-Homik-joins-for-NBL Jets stronger as Homik joins for NBL]</ref> However, he played just two games after suffering a broken left ankle.<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/5172556/Mike-Homiks-season-over-for-Manawatu-Jets Mike Homik's season over for Manawatu Jets]</ref> He re-joined the Jets for the [[2012 New Zealand NBL season|2012 season]].<ref name=\"retire\" />\n\nFor the [[2013 New Zealand NBL season]], Homik played for the [[Wellington Saints]].<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/8336977/Wizard-Mr-President-join-Saints-cast Wizard, Mr President join Saints cast]</ref><ref>[http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/sport/128737/wellington-saints-sign-veteran-mike-homik Wellington Saints sign veteran Mike Homik]</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Homik had a one-game stint with the Manawatu Jets to help them deal with numerous injuries.<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/67681219/its-just-like-old-times-for-jets-imports It's just like old times for Jets imports]</ref><ref>[http://www.foxsportspulse.com/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&pID=193586012&client=11-8336-114269-356729-23059886 Player statistics for Mike Homik]</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nOff the basketball court, Homik has been a stunt man in films such as ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]'' as well as various television commercials.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10713640 Basketball: Power forward's double life as a stuntman]</ref> In 2016, Homik played the role of a villain in the [[Bollywood]] film [[Mohenjo Daro (film)|Mohenjo Daro]] starring [[Hrithik Roshan]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Hinton | first = Marc | url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/67543302/tall-black-centurion-casey-frank-returns-for-another-crack-at-the-nbl | title = Tall Black centurion Casey Frank returns for another crack at the NBL | date = 30 March 2015 | accessdate = 31 March 2015 | work = Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060824051930/http://www.basketball.org.nz/index.cgi?sID=43&intArticleID=674&det=1 Basketball New Zealand profile]\n*[http://www.foxsportspulse.com/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&pID=193586012&client=11-8336-114269-356729-23059886 NZNBL stats]\n\n{{2006 New Zealand Commonwealth Games team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Homik, Mike}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Auckland Stars players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2006 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Manawatu Jets players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:People educated at St John's College, Hamilton]]\n[[Category:Waikato Pistons players]]\n[[Category:Wellington Saints players]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in basketball]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Mike Homik\n| image = \n| caption = \n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_cm = 204\n| weight_kg = 115\n| league = \n| team = \n| number = \n| nationality = New Zealand\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|7|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n| high_school = [[St John's College, Hamilton|St John's College]]<br>(Hamilton, New Zealand)\n| college = [[West Valley College|West Valley JC]] (1997\u20131999)<br>[[College of Idaho]] (2000\u20132002)\n| career_start = 1996\n| career_end = 2015\n| years1 = 1996\u20131997\n| team1 = [[Waikato Pistons|Waikato Warriors]]\n| years2 = 2003\u20132005\n| team2 = [[Auckland Stars]]\n| years3 = 2003\u20132004\n| team3 = [[New Zealand Breakers]]\n| years4 = 2006\n| team4 = [[Harbour Heat]]\n| years5 = 2007\u20132010\n| team5 = [[Waikato Pistons]]\n| years6 = 2007\u20132008\n| team6 = [[Perth Wildcats]]\n| years7 = 2011\u20132012\n| team7 = [[Manawatu Jets]]\n| years8 = 2013\n| team8 = [[Wellington Saints]]\n| years9 = 2015\n| team9 = Manawatu Jets\n| highlights =\n*4\u00d7 [[List of New Zealand NBL champions|NZNBL champion]] (2004, 2005, 2008, 2009)\n}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{NZL}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2006 Commonwealth Games|2006 Melbourne]] | Team Competition}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n'''Michael Homik''' (born 6 July 1978) is a New Zealand former [[basketball]] player. He played 14 seasons in the [[National Basketball League (New Zealand)|National Basketball League]] (NBL) and won four [[List of New Zealand NBL champions|championships]]. He also played for the [[New Zealand national basketball team|Tall Blacks]] and won a silver medal at the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]].\n\n==Early life==\nHomik was born and raised in [[Hamilton, New Zealand]], where he attended [[St John's College, Hamilton|St John's College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/2920515/Head-and-shoulders-above-rest |title=Head and shoulders above rest |first=Daniel |last=Richardson |work=Stuff.co.nz |publisher=Fairfax Media |date=1 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tyugts8h?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/2920515/Head-and-shoulders-above-rest |archivedate=4 November 2010 |accessdate=4 November 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=retire>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/7023398/Jets-lose-retired-Homik-as-stunt-job-beckons Jets lose retired Homik as stunt job beckons]</ref>\n\n==Basketball career==\nIn 1996, Homik debuted in the NBL for the [[Waikato Pistons|Waikato Warriors]].<ref name=bbnz>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060824051930/http://www.basketball.org.nz/index.cgi?sID=43&intArticleID=674&det=1 Mike Homik Basketball NZ profile]</ref> He played seven games in both 1996 and 1997, before moving to the United States for college.<ref name=\"bbnz\" /> He played two seasons of [[college basketball]] for [[West Valley College]] before transferring to [[College of Idaho|Albertson College of Idaho]].\n\nHomik returned from the United States in 2003 and joined the [[Auckland Stars]].<ref>[http://www.olympic.org.nz/athletes/michael-homik/ Michael Homik NZ Olympic profile]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nzgirl.co.nz/know/2253/ |title=2003 NBL Teams and Draw |access-date=18 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907144718/http://www.nzgirl.co.nz/know/2253/ |archive-date=7 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He later joined the [[New Zealand Breakers]] for their inaugural season in the [[National Basketball League (Australia)|Australian NBL]] in [[2003\u201304 NBL season|2003/04]]. In 2004 and 2005, he was a member of the Stars' back-to-back championship teams.\n\nFor the [[2006 New Zealand NBL season]], Homik played for the [[Harbour Heat]]. He went on to spend the next four NBL seasons playing for the [[Waikato Pistons]], including winning championships in 2008 and 2009. During this time, he played a second season in the Australian NBL, this time with the [[Perth Wildcats]] in [[2007\u201308 NBL season|2007/08]].<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/Sport/NBL-preseason-close-to-tipoff/2007/07/27/1185339243592.html NBL pre-season close to tip-off]</ref>\n\nFor the [[2011 New Zealand NBL season]], Homik joined the [[Manawatu Jets]].<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/basketball/4434739/Jets-stronger-as-Homik-joins-for-NBL Jets stronger as Homik joins for NBL]</ref> However, he played just two games after suffering a broken left ankle.<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/5172556/Mike-Homiks-season-over-for-Manawatu-Jets Mike Homik's season over for Manawatu Jets]</ref> He re-joined the Jets for the [[2012 New Zealand NBL season|2012 season]].<ref name=\"retire\" />\n\nFor the [[2013 New Zealand NBL season]], Homik played for the [[Wellington Saints]].<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/8336977/Wizard-Mr-President-join-Saints-cast Wizard, Mr President join Saints cast]</ref><ref>[http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/sport/128737/wellington-saints-sign-veteran-mike-homik Wellington Saints sign veteran Mike Homik]</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Homik had a one-game stint with the Manawatu Jets to help them deal with numerous injuries.<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/67681219/its-just-like-old-times-for-jets-imports It's just like old times for Jets imports]</ref><ref>[http://www.foxsportspulse.com/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&pID=193586012&client=11-8336-114269-356729-23059886 Player statistics for Mike Homik]</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nOff the basketball court, Homik has been a stunt man in films such as ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]'' as well as various television commercials.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10713640 Basketball: Power forward's double life as a stuntman]</ref> In 2016, Homik played the role of a villain in the [[Bollywood]] film [[Mohenjo Daro (film)|Mohenjo Daro]] starring [[Hrithik Roshan]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Hinton | first = Marc | url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/67543302/tall-black-centurion-casey-frank-returns-for-another-crack-at-the-nbl | title = Tall Black centurion Casey Frank returns for another crack at the NBL | date = 30 March 2015 | accessdate = 31 March 2015 | work = Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060824051930/http://www.basketball.org.nz/index.cgi?sID=43&intArticleID=674&det=1 Basketball New Zealand profile]\n*[http://www.foxsportspulse.com/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&pID=193586012&client=11-8336-114269-356729-23059886 NZNBL stats]\n\n{{2006 New Zealand Commonwealth Games team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Homik, Mike}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Auckland Stars players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2006 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Manawatu Jets players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:People educated at St John's College, Hamilton]]\n[[Category:Waikato Pistons players]]\n[[Category:Wellington Saints players]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in basketball]]\n", "name_user": "DaHuzyBru", "label": "safe", "comment": "combined medals into infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Homik"}
{"title_page": "Chengalpattu district", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=March 2019}}\n{{About|the district|its headquarters|Chengalpattu}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Chengalpattu District\n| official_name                   = \n| nickname                        = Chengai District\n| settlement_type                 = District\n| image_skyline                   = Chengalpat lake.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Kolavai Lake on the outskirts of Chengalpattu\n| image_map                       = Chengalpattu district location map.svg\n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| coordinates                     = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[File:TamilNadu Logo.svg|22px]] [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Region]]\n| subdivision_name2               = \n| subdivision_type3               = Municipalities\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Chengalpattu]]\n| established_title               = Established\n| established_date                = 29 November 2019\n| founder                         = [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami]]\n| named_for                       = Chengalpet town\n| parts_type                      = [[Taluka|Taluks]]\n| parts                           = [[Chengalpattu taluk|Chengalpattu]], [[Cheyyur taluk|Cheyyur]], [[Madurantakam taluk|Madurantakam]], [[Tambaram taluk|Tambaram]], [[Thiruporur taluk|Thiruporur]], [[Tirukalukundram taluk|Tirukalukundram]],  [[Vandalur|Vandalur]],\n [[Pallavaram taluk|Pallavaram]]\n| seat_type                       = Headquarters\n| seat                            = [[Chengalpattu]]\n| seat1_type                      = Largest City\n| seat1                           = [[Pallavaram]] and [[Tambaram]]\n| government_type                 = District Administration\n| governing_body                  = Chengalpattu District Collectorate\n| leader_title1                   = [[District Collector]]\n| leader_name1                    = A.John Louis,[[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]]\n| leader_title2                   = [[Superintendent of Police]]\n| leader_name2                    = T.Kannan,  [[Indian Police Service|IPS]]\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=news7>{{cite AV media |title=\u0b9a\u0bc6\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0baa\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1 \u0bae\u0bbe\u0bb5\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc8 \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bc1! |language=Tamil |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AioOsBxBoHw |publisher=[[News7 Tamil]] |date=28 November 2019 |access-date=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = 2,945\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = 2,556,423\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_rank                 = 8th\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=news7 />\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 603XXX,600XXX\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| area_code                       = 044\n| registration_plate              = TN-19, TN-14, TN-22, TN-85 and TN-11\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n'''Chengalpattu District''' is one of the 38 [[List of districts of Tamil Nadu|districts]] of [[Tamil Nadu]]. The district headquarters is located at [[Chengalpattu]]. Chengalpattu district came into existence on 29 November 2019 when it was carved out of [[Kanchipuram district]] after the announcement about the bifurcation of districts on 18 July 2019.\n\n[[File:Chengalpattu Collector office.jpg|thumb|Chengalpattu Collector office]]\n<br />\n\n== Geography ==\nChengalpattu district shares borders with [[Bay of Bengal]] in the east and the districts [[Chennai district|Chennai]] in the north, [[Kanchipuram district|Kanchipuram]] and [[Tiruvannamalai district| Tiruvannamalai]] in the west and [[Villupuram district|Villupuram]] in the south.\n\nChengalpattu  is very close to the state capital Chennai. National Highway 45 runs through this district from north part of this district from Tirusulam to south end of this district Thozhuppedu. The northern part of the district  are suburbs/extended sububrs of the Chennai city while the southern part of the district is more rural in nature.\n\nThe district has a number of lakes and the [[Maduranthakam lake]] is the largest lake in Chengalpattu district and is the second largest lake in tamilnadu. \n\nTwo Check dams are present across the river palar in this district. One at eesoor and Vallipuram villages of madurantakam taluk and Thirukkazhukkundram taluks. Second one is at Vayalur near Kalpakkam of Cheyyur Taluk which was built in the year 2019. \n\nThis district has a coastal area from kanathur in north to kadapakkam in South. Major places in this coastal areas are Kovalam, thiruvidanthai, vadanemmeli, muttukkadu, mamallapuram, kalpakkam, sadurangapattinam, kadalur, koovathur, edaikazhinadu and kadapakkam.\n\n== Economy ==\n=== Industries ===\nDue to its proximity to Chennai, the district hosts a number of manufacturing industries and IT parks.  Both of these industries are present in two major corridors, GST road and OMR.  Siruseri [[SIPCOT IT Park]]  is situated in OMR and it comes under Thirupporur taluk. [[Madras Export Processing Zone]] has a few IT companies and apparel companies in GST road and it comes under  Tambaram Taluk. The area around Tiruneermalai under pallavaram taluk has a number of small and medium sides leather processing units. [[Maraimalai Nagar]] has a manufacturing unit of Ford motors. Mahindra World City has a manufacturing unit of BMW along with apparel units and Mahindra Research valley, which is the R&D division of Mahindra & Mahindra automobiles.\nThe Kalpakkam atomic power stations fall under this district. There is an ultra mega power project proposed in Cheyyur.\n\n=== Agriculture ===\nAgriculture is more prevalent in the southern part of the district. Madurantakam, cheyyur and Thirukkazhukkundram taluks are major producers of rice in this district.\nSugarcane also grown in some parts of the district. Tamil Nadu Government has a cooperative sugar mills in Padalam village of Madurantakam taluk.\nGroundnuts also grown as major crop in areas where/when there is scarcity of water or shortage of rainfall. Cheyyur and Thirupporur taluks are well known for money crops such as groundnuts, Urid dhal, Moong dhal, Seasame, etc.\n\nVegetables such as brinjal, ladies finger also grown in Thirupporur, Thirukkazhukkundram and Madurantakam regions.\n\nWatermelons are cultivated in Kodur, Cheyyur and its surrounding areas during summer.\n\nBeatel leaves are produced in Karunguzhi.\n\n=== Fishing ===\nThere are number of fishing villages along the coast and fishing has been practiced here for centuries. The fishing activity is of a small scale with no fishing harbour present. But, the number of people employed by this industry remain high.\n\n=== Services ===\nDue to the high percentage of middle class population present, there is a thriving industry of restaurants, theatres in the district.  The ECR along the coast acts as a leisure and entertainment corridor. The hotels and resorts in this road employ a large number of people.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Chengalpattu district map.png|thumb|Proposed map of Panchayat divisions of Chengalpattu district]]\nChengalpattu district is well connected with all means of transport such as roadways, railways.\n\n===Roadways===\n\nThis district has well developed roads interconnecting all major towns, villages to the district capital. NH45 runs north- south along the entire length of the district and is the arterial road.  Part of the Chennai Outer ring road comes under this district.East coast road runs along the Bay of Bengal and connects the coastal districts of Tamilnadu. Old Mahabalipuram Road runs adjacent to ECR and hosts a number of industries. All these roads run along a north-south axis.\n\nOther major roads are Vandalur-Kelambakkam Road, Pallavaram-Thoraipakkam radial road,Pallavaram-Kundrathur-Poonamallee Road , Tambaram-Velachery road, Tambaram- Mudichur road , Guduvancheri-Nellikuppam road, Urapakkam-Adhanur road, Singaperumal koil-Shriperumbudur road, Chengalpattu- Thirupporur Highway, Chengalpattu-Mamallapuram road, Bukkathurai-Uthiramerur road, Padalam-Cheyyur road, Padalam-Vedanthangal road, Karunguzhi-Thirukkazhukundram road, Madurantakam-Vennagupattu road, Cheyyur-Sothupakkam-Vandavasi road, Thozhuppedu-Orathy-Thindivanam road. These roads primarily run along the east -west direction connecting the north-south corridors mentioned above.\n\nApart from these major roads, this district has many PWD roads which helps in connecting small villages to taluk or district headquarters.\n\n===Railways===\n\nChengalpattu district has a strong presence of rail network. The Chennai-Villupuram line runs along the district roughly parallel to the GST road. There is a branch line from Chengalpet to Arakkonam. Long distance trains from Chennai to south Tamilnadu travel via this route. Almost all trains stop at both Tambaram and Chengalpattu. Other than long distance trains there are regional passenger services connecting Chennai with Puducherry and Villupuram. \n\n\nThe suburban services from Chennai beach upto Tambaram were started in the year 1931. The areas along the suburban line grew in population primarily due to the presence of the line. A large number of people working in Chennai settled around Pallavaram, Chromepet, Tambaram areas. Currently the suburban services are operated upto Kanchipuram, although most services start at Tambaram and a few at Chengalpattu. Tambaram has a EMU carshed to cater to this section.\n\n\nThe tracks are quadrapuled from Chennai Egmore until Tambaram and doubled beyond Tambaram. Tripling the section between Tambaram and Chengalpattu is under progress. \n\nTambaram railway station acts as a third railway terminal for Chennai city and a few trains originate from here. There are a few trains originating from Chengalpattu stations as well.\n\nChennai Metro rail limited (CMRL) has proposed extension of Metro line from Airport Metro till Kilambakkam via Pallavaram, Tambaram, Perungalathur, Vandalur to ease passenger commute.\n\n===Airways===\n\nThe Chennai International Airport is located here opposite the Tirusulam Railway station, with the cargo terminal located at the adjacent Meenambakkam. Chennai International Airport (IATA: MAA, ICAO: VOMM) is the primary airport serving the city of Chennai. The airport is the regional headquarters of the Airports Authority of India for South India comprising the states of Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, Karnataka and Kerala and the union territories of Puducherry and Lakshadweep.\n\n== Tourism ==\n\nMajor tourist spots in Chengalpattu district are as follows:\n\n1. Mamallapuram rock cut cave temples built by pallavas.\n\n2. Vandalur Arignar anna zoological park.\n\n3. Vedanthangal birds sanctuary.\n\n4. VGP golden beach, Kovalam surf point, Mamallapuram beach.\n\n5. Sadurangapattinam Dutch fort.\n\n6. Edaikazhinadu backwaters.\n\n7. Edaikazhinadu Portuguese fort remains.\n\n8. Thirukazhukundram vedagiriswarar temple.\n\n9. Boat House, Paramankeni Near Cheyyur.\n\n10. Wonderla Theme Park is under construction at Illalur, Thiruporur.\n11. Melmaruvathur Adhiparasakthi Siddar peedam - Temple\n\n== Administration ==\nChengalpattu District has 3 Revenue Divisions\n\n* '''Tambaram Revenue Division:''' [[Pallavaram|Pallavaram taluk]], [[Tambaram taluk]],[[Vandalur|Vandalur taluk]]\n\n* '''Chengalpattu Revenue Division:''' [[Chengalpattu taluk]], [[Thiruporur taluk]], [[Tirukalukundram taluk]]\n\n* '''Madurantakam Revenue Division:''' [[Madurantakam taluk]], [[Cheyyur taluk]]\n\nPallavaram and Tambaram taluks lies in the [[Chennai Metropolitan Area]].\n\n<br />\n\n=== District Panchayat ===\nChengalpattu district has 16 district panchayat wards details of which are in <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kancheepuram.nic.in/local-body-ward-delimitation-2020-chengalpattu-district/|title=Local Body Ward Delimitation \u2013 2020 \u2013 Chengalpattu District {{!}} Kancheepuram District,Government of Tamilnadu {{!}} City of Thousand Temples {{!}} India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n===Municipalities===\n\nChengalpattu District has 8 Municipalities and 1 Cantonment Board\n\n* [[Chengalpattu]]\n* [[Madurantakam]]\n* [[Tambaram]] \n* [[Pallavaram]] (Pallavaram municipality includes [[Chromepet]] and [[Keelkattalai]] too)\n*[[St.Thomas Mount-cum-Pallavaram|St.Thomas Mount cum Pallavaram Cantonment Board]]\n* [[Pammal]]\n* [[Anakaputhur]]\n* [[Maraimalainagar]]\n* [[Sembakkam]]\n\n===Panchayat Unions===\n\nChengalpattu District has 8 Panchayat Unions\n\n*[[Kattangulathur block|Kattangulathur]]\n*[[St. Thomas Mount block|St. Thomas Mount]]\n*[[Thirupporur block|Thirupporur]]\n*[[Tirukalukundram block|Tirukalukundram]]\n*[[Lathur block|Lathur]]\n*[[Chithamur block|Chithamur]]\n*[[Madurantakam block|Madurantakam]]\n*[[Acharapakkam block|Acharapakkam]]\n\n===Town Panchayats===\n\nChengalpattu District has 12 Town Panchayats details of which are in <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kancheepuram.nic.in/local-body-ward-delimitation-2020-chengalpattu-district/|title=Local Body Ward Delimitation \u2013 2020 \u2013 Chengalpattu District {{!}} Kancheepuram District,Government of Tamilnadu {{!}} City of Thousand Temples {{!}} India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n#[[Acharapakkam]]\n#[[Chitlapakkam]]\n#[[Edaikazhinadu]]\n#[[Karunguzhi]]\n#[[Madambakkam]]\n#[[Mamallapuram]]\n#[[Nandivaram-Guduvancheri]]\n#[[Peerkankaranai]]\n#[[Perungalathur]]\n#[[Thiruneermalai]]\n#[[Thiruporur]]\n#[[Tirukalukundram]]\n\n===Village Panchayats===\n\nChengalpattu District has 359 Rural Village Panchayats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kancheepuram.nic.in/local-body-ward-delimitation-2020-chengalpattu-district/|title=Local Body Ward Delimitation \u2013 2020 \u2013 Chengalpattu District {{!}} Kancheepuram District,Government of Tamilnadu {{!}} City of Thousand Temples {{!}} India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n[[Mudichur]], [[Vandalur]], [[Pozhichalur]], [[Tirusulam]], [[Cowl Bazaar]], [[Medavakkam]], [[Nanmangalam]],[[Kovilambakkam]], [[Agaramthen]], [[Mappedu]], [[Sithalapakkam]], [[Kovilanchery]], [[Ponmar]], [[Mambakkam]], [[Thalambur]], [[Siruseri]], [[Muttukadu]], [[Vandalur]], [[Urapakkam]], [[Singaperumal Koil]], [[Paranur]], [[Kodur, Tamil Nadu|Kodur]], [[Koovathur]], [[Nedumaram]], [[Seekinankuppam]], [[Veerabogam]],Manamai,Padur, kolatthur, cheyyur\n\n===Assembly constituencies===\n\nChengalpattu District has 6 State Assembly Constituencies and 2 State Assembly constituencies partially from Chennai.\n\n*[[Chengalpattu (state assembly constituency)|Chengalpattu]] \n*[[Tambaram (state assembly constituency)|Tambaram]] \n*[[Pallavaram (state assembly constituency)|Pallavaram]] (Except [[Meenambakkam]])\n*[[Maduranthakam (state assembly constituency)|Maduranthakam]]\n*[[Cheyyur (state assembly constituency)|Cheyyur]]\n*[[Thiruporur (state assembly constituency)|Thiruporur]]\n*[[Alandur (state assembly constituency)|Alandur]] - few villages like [[Moovarasampettai|Moovarasampattu]] and [[Cowl Bazaar]] only\n*[[Sholinganallur (state assembly constituency)|Sholinganallur]] - few villages like [[Kovilambakkam]] [[Nanmangalam]] and [[Medavakkam]] only\n\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tenkasi-chengalpattu-to-become-new-districts/article28547194.ece|title=Tenkasi, Chengalpattu to become new districts|date=2019-07-18|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-07-18|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Tamil Nadu}}\n\n[[Category:Districts of Tamil Nadu]]\n\n\n{{TamilNadu-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2019}}\n{{About|the district|its headquarters|Chengalpattu}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Chengalpattu District\n| official_name                   = \n| nickname                        = Chengai District\n| settlement_type                 = District\n| image_skyline                   = Chengalpat lake.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Kolavai Lake on the outskirts of Chengalpattu\n| image_map                       = Chengalpattu district location map.svg\n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| coordinates                     = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[File:TamilNadu Logo.svg|22px]] [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Region]]\n| subdivision_name2               = \n| subdivision_type3               = Municipalities\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Chengalpattu]]\n| established_title               = Established\n| established_date              